1
00:00:29,488 --> 00:00:34,368
Excuse me. Sorry. I'm sorry.

2
00:00:34,410 --> 00:00:36,162
Excuse me. Coming through.

3
00:00:38,038 --> 00:00:39,957
[Thaddeus] <i>Tonight, so-called
magician Lionel Shrike</i>

4
00:00:39,999 --> 00:00:42,543
<i>is making another sad
attempt for attention</i>

5
00:00:42,585 --> 00:00:45,963
<i>by performing what he calls
an impossible feat.</i>

6
00:00:46,005 --> 00:00:49,425
<i>The safe is made of
the strongest iron.</i>

7
00:00:49,467 --> 00:00:52,636
<i>It can't be sawed through or pried.</i>

8
00:00:52,678 --> 00:00:57,016
<i>Yet, Lionel Shrike thinks
he's able to escape.</i>

9
00:00:57,058 --> 00:00:58,934
Dad! Dad!

10
00:01:00,394 --> 00:01:03,773
Hey, buddy.
You made it, huh?

11
00:01:03,814 --> 00:01:07,234
Now, see that seat there?

12
00:01:07,276 --> 00:01:08,819
It's the best
seat in the house.

13
00:01:08,861 --> 00:01:13,115
Is Lionel Shrike the kind
of magician who can pull this off?

14
00:01:13,157 --> 00:01:16,076
<i>Or is he actually
in over his head?</i>

15
00:01:16,118 --> 00:01:17,745
We'll see about that.

16
00:01:17,787 --> 00:01:20,164
- What's the matter?
- I don't want you to go.

17
00:01:20,206 --> 00:01:22,416
Dylan, come on.
We talked about this.

18
00:01:22,458 --> 00:01:24,794
Remember?
This is what I do.

19
00:01:24,835 --> 00:01:27,379
I got to prove all
those naysayers wrong.

20
00:01:27,421 --> 00:01:30,257
Okay? Besides...

21
00:01:30,299 --> 00:01:33,385
[whispers] I always keep
something up my sleeve.

22
00:01:33,427 --> 00:01:35,554
Now, got your watch
like your dad's?

23
00:01:36,263 --> 00:01:39,099
- Okay. How many seconds?
- Three hundred.

24
00:01:39,141 --> 00:01:41,852
Three hundred. Maybe a few less.

25
00:01:43,729 --> 00:01:47,066
Mmm.
I love you so much.

26
00:01:48,859 --> 00:01:51,779
[whispers]
Okay. See you later, big man.

27
00:01:51,821 --> 00:01:56,492
[announcer] Ladies and gentlemen,
Lionel Shrike!

28
00:01:56,534 --> 00:01:57,993
[crowd cheering]

29
00:01:58,035 --> 00:02:00,037
[Thaddeus] Will he be able
to hold his breath?

30
00:02:00,079 --> 00:02:03,791
Will he be able to
somehow escape the safe?

31
00:02:07,169 --> 00:02:09,588
[crowd] Three, two, one...

32
00:02:12,341 --> 00:02:14,260
[crowd cheering]

33
00:02:14,969 --> 00:02:16,428
Two, three,

34
00:02:16,470 --> 00:02:21,100
four, five, six,
seven, eight...

35
00:02:21,934 --> 00:02:28,983
296... 297, 298, 299, 300.

36
00:02:32,403 --> 00:02:35,197
303, 304...

37
00:02:36,282 --> 00:02:37,950
[Thaddeus]
<i>It's five minutes now,</i>

38
00:02:38,909 --> 00:02:43,414
<i>and we have not seen or heard
anything from Lionel Shrike yet.</i>

39
00:02:43,455 --> 00:02:44,623
Move!

40
00:02:44,665 --> 00:02:45,916
[crowd murmuring]

41
00:02:45,958 --> 00:02:47,084
Dad!

42
00:02:47,126 --> 00:02:48,294
[ambulance siren wailing]

43
00:02:48,335 --> 00:02:50,838
Dad! Dad!

44
00:02:52,756 --> 00:02:54,174
Let go of me!

45
00:02:54,967 --> 00:02:56,176
Dad!

46
00:02:57,428 --> 00:02:59,305
[sobs] No! Dad!

47
00:03:00,389 --> 00:03:02,474
Dad! Let go!

48
00:03:03,601 --> 00:03:04,852
Find him!

49
00:03:06,687 --> 00:03:08,022
[inaudible]

50
00:03:24,997 --> 00:03:26,248
[Thaddeus] <i>The Eye.</i>

51
00:03:26,999 --> 00:03:28,959
<i>It may not lie...</i>

52
00:03:29,001 --> 00:03:32,546
<i>But don't think for a moment
that it can't be lied to.</i>

53
00:03:34,298 --> 00:03:37,176
<i>Seeing is believing.</i>

54
00:03:37,218 --> 00:03:39,178
<i>But is it truth?</i>

55
00:03:39,220 --> 00:03:43,724
<i>People see the Horsemen
as noble Robin Hoods. Are they?</i>

56
00:03:43,766 --> 00:03:46,977
<i>Or are they common thieves?</i>

57
00:03:47,019 --> 00:03:48,896
<i>Depends on your point of view.</i>

58
00:03:49,563 --> 00:03:51,106
<i>Here's what you know.</i>

59
00:03:51,148 --> 00:03:54,777
<i>They robbed a bank in Paris
from a stage in Las Vegas.</i>

60
00:03:54,818 --> 00:03:56,487
<i>They fleeced
an insurance magnate</i>

61
00:03:56,528 --> 00:03:58,113
<i>of hundreds of
millions of dollars</i>

62
00:03:58,155 --> 00:04:00,824
<i>and disappeared from
a roof in New York.</i>

63
00:04:00,866 --> 00:04:05,162
<i>Always showering their
devoted fans with money.</i>

64
00:04:05,204 --> 00:04:07,122
<i>Here's what you don't know.</i>

65
00:04:07,164 --> 00:04:09,333
<i>They left one man behind.</i>

66
00:04:09,375 --> 00:04:12,836
<i>Framed. Holding the bag. Me.</i>

67
00:04:14,421 --> 00:04:16,799
<i>Are you listening, Horsemen?</i>

68
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:20,052
<i>When you emerge, and you will,</i>

69
00:04:21,095 --> 00:04:24,181
<i>I will be there waiting.</i>

70
00:04:24,223 --> 00:04:29,478
<i>Because mark my words,
you will get what's coming to you.</i>

71
00:04:29,520 --> 00:04:31,939
<i>In ways you can't expect.</i>

72
00:04:32,731 --> 00:04:34,942
<i>But very much deserve.</i>

73
00:04:34,984 --> 00:04:41,824
<i>Because one thing I believe in
is an eye for an eye.</i>

74
00:05:10,436 --> 00:05:11,854
[exhales]

75
00:05:57,649 --> 00:05:59,193
[door locks]

76
00:05:59,234 --> 00:06:01,111
[man] <i>Welcome, Daniel Atlas.</i>

77
00:06:02,196 --> 00:06:03,530
Who am I speaking to?

78
00:06:04,907 --> 00:06:06,992
I asked to see the face
behind all of this.

79
00:06:07,910 --> 00:06:12,372
<i>You've asked many questions.
And registered many complaints.</i>

80
00:06:12,414 --> 00:06:14,375
<i>You can rest assured
that we've heard you.</i>

81
00:06:14,416 --> 00:06:15,959
- Have you? Because I don't--
- [whispering voices]

82
00:06:16,001 --> 00:06:17,377
<i>- Trust?</i>
- No.

83
00:06:17,419 --> 00:06:20,172
<i>Your leader?
Your fellow Horsemen?</i>

84
00:06:20,214 --> 00:06:21,715
<i>Perhaps even us?</i>

85
00:06:21,757 --> 00:06:25,761
I don't like that we've been
living in hiding for a year.

86
00:06:25,803 --> 00:06:28,055
I don't like that every message
I get from Dylan is,

87
00:06:28,097 --> 00:06:30,766
"Wait. Be patient.
The Eye has a plan."

88
00:06:30,808 --> 00:06:33,227
<i>- Wait. Be patient.</i>
- [chuckles dryly]

89
00:06:33,268 --> 00:06:34,520
<i>The Eye has a plan.</i>

90
00:06:34,561 --> 00:06:37,564
This is games
and it's not working for me.

91
00:06:37,606 --> 00:06:39,149
[whispering voices continue]

92
00:06:39,191 --> 00:06:42,569
<i>You feel it is you who should be
leading the Horsemen, not Dylan.</i>

93
00:06:44,363 --> 00:06:48,117
<i>If that is what you desire,
stay the course.</i>

94
00:06:48,158 --> 00:06:50,202
<i>Trust that your unique talents</i>

95
00:06:50,244 --> 00:06:54,081
<i>and remarkable mind
will not go unrecognized.</i>

96
00:06:54,123 --> 00:06:56,750
<i>We have a new mission
for the Horsemen.</i>

97
00:06:56,792 --> 00:06:59,920
<i>Dylan has a plan
and will gather you together soon.</i>

98
00:07:01,130 --> 00:07:02,798
[voices] <i>Now leave!</i>

99
00:07:09,555 --> 00:07:11,098
[phone ringing]

100
00:07:13,559 --> 00:07:16,728
[indistinct chatter]

101
00:07:16,770 --> 00:07:19,606
[Austin]...North Carolina,
Florida, Maryland, Maine.

102
00:07:19,648 --> 00:07:21,567
We're talking the entire
eastern seaboard.

103
00:07:21,608 --> 00:07:23,569
I need to see some results.

104
00:07:23,610 --> 00:07:25,446
Oh, hey. Oh, sorry.

105
00:07:25,487 --> 00:07:27,573
Just real quick. Can I have you
for a couple of minutes?

106
00:07:27,614 --> 00:07:29,283
I'm right in the middle
of something, Dylan.

107
00:07:29,324 --> 00:07:31,702
No, I know. It's okay. Hey. Hey,
everybody. Sorry. Sorry about that.

108
00:07:31,743 --> 00:07:34,371
[sighs]
Call the mayor.

109
00:07:34,413 --> 00:07:36,832
Thanks a lot.
Twins, huh? Good.

110
00:07:37,624 --> 00:07:39,084
Is he coming?

111
00:07:39,126 --> 00:07:41,253
Look, I wouldn't have
brought you out of that meeting

112
00:07:41,295 --> 00:07:42,796
unless it was something important.

113
00:07:42,838 --> 00:07:45,257
It's about the Horsemen.

114
00:07:45,299 --> 00:07:48,469
Something's happening here
and it's happening now.

115
00:07:48,510 --> 00:07:51,263
Message boards.
Elite magic society.

116
00:07:51,305 --> 00:07:53,765
There is chatter going on
about the Horsemen

117
00:07:53,807 --> 00:07:57,102
and something happening with Octa,
the giant software company.

118
00:07:57,144 --> 00:07:58,187
I know what Octa is.

119
00:07:58,228 --> 00:07:59,938
I'm sorry, ma'am,
but two months ago

120
00:07:59,980 --> 00:08:01,982
we sent men to Philadelphia
because he knew...

121
00:08:02,024 --> 00:08:04,359
- And I said that I was wrong.
- He knew that the Horsemen

122
00:08:04,401 --> 00:08:06,028
were going to hit
the Euro-Atlantic Banking Summit.

123
00:08:06,069 --> 00:08:07,112
- I have proof.
- Let him talk.

124
00:08:07,154 --> 00:08:09,406
Thank you.
Communications.

125
00:08:09,448 --> 00:08:13,493
Contact between who I think
might be Daniel Atlas

126
00:08:13,535 --> 00:08:16,246
and who may be Merritt McKinney.

127
00:08:16,288 --> 00:08:19,666
And what do you have?
Emails? Cell phones? Any transcripts?

128
00:08:19,708 --> 00:08:21,919
- Pigeons.
- What?

129
00:08:21,960 --> 00:08:24,296
I'm sorry,
you mean stool pigeons?

130
00:08:24,338 --> 00:08:27,007
No, I mean actual pigeon pigeons.
Like carrier pigeons.

131
00:08:27,049 --> 00:08:30,052
- Okay? Magicians work with pigeons.
- Doves.

132
00:08:31,220 --> 00:08:32,554
Stay with me.

133
00:08:33,639 --> 00:08:35,849
This pigeon, right here...

134
00:08:35,891 --> 00:08:38,518
There's Daniel Atlas.
Same pigeon.

135
00:08:38,560 --> 00:08:39,686
East Village.

136
00:08:39,728 --> 00:08:41,355
Same pigeon, West Village.

137
00:08:41,396 --> 00:08:44,191
42nd Street, pigeon. 65th Street.

138
00:08:44,233 --> 00:08:47,152
All the way up to the
George Washington Bridge

139
00:08:47,194 --> 00:08:51,823
on a sail boat with a guy that looks
just like Merritt McKinney.

140
00:08:51,865 --> 00:08:53,325
And what does this all mean?

141
00:08:53,367 --> 00:08:55,827
I know what it means.
It means nothing. It's bullshit.

142
00:08:55,869 --> 00:08:57,621
- Could you sing a new song?
- No.

143
00:08:57,663 --> 00:08:59,706
How is it that two years ago
you were so close...

144
00:08:59,748 --> 00:09:02,417
[Dylan] You think I went out of my way
to screw up my own investigation?

145
00:09:02,459 --> 00:09:03,669
You think I'm
that big of an idiot?

146
00:09:03,710 --> 00:09:05,254
You know what I think now?
I think you're smart,

147
00:09:05,295 --> 00:09:06,505
but you want everybody else
to think that you're an idiot.

148
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:08,549
[Austin] Okay, stop.

149
00:09:08,590 --> 00:09:11,677
Cowan, I know I'm new here,
but as far as I can tell,

150
00:09:11,718 --> 00:09:14,012
people who don't even know you,
think you're an asshole.

151
00:09:14,972 --> 00:09:16,390
- And you?
- Ma'am.

152
00:09:16,431 --> 00:09:20,394
You don't know me, but my first year
in the Academy, you gave a talk.

153
00:09:20,435 --> 00:09:24,898
The "long game" you called it.
You talked about a moral compass.

154
00:09:24,940 --> 00:09:27,150
About how you believed
in yours immutably.

155
00:09:28,944 --> 00:09:34,324
And I thought to myself, "That guy.
One day, I want to be that guy."

156
00:09:35,909 --> 00:09:38,495
And now... A pigeon?

157
00:09:38,537 --> 00:09:40,747
Technically, it was a few pigeons,
but I hear what you're saying.

158
00:09:40,789 --> 00:09:42,374
[sighs] Okay. So here's what
I'm going to do.

159
00:09:42,416 --> 00:09:45,460
You want to take a vacation day?
Go on your own? Fine.

160
00:09:45,502 --> 00:09:48,839
But I'm not going to devote resources
to another snipe hunt.

161
00:09:48,880 --> 00:09:52,050
I came to clean this mess up,
not add to it. I'm sorry.

162
00:09:52,092 --> 00:09:55,595
Boss, thank you. I promise you,
it won't be a snipe hunt.

163
00:09:55,637 --> 00:09:57,723
We're gonna get those Horsemen.

164
00:09:58,098 --> 00:09:59,224
She's great.

165
00:09:59,266 --> 00:10:02,477
The problem is when you're
two people at the same time,

166
00:10:02,519 --> 00:10:04,021
one of them is bound
to trip the other.

167
00:10:04,062 --> 00:10:07,316
And when that happens,
I will be there.

168
00:10:07,899 --> 00:10:09,151
Duly noted.

169
00:10:19,453 --> 00:10:20,912
[door closes]

170
00:10:23,415 --> 00:10:25,500
[clattering]

171
00:10:30,547 --> 00:10:32,174
- Oh. Hi!
- Who are you?

172
00:10:32,215 --> 00:10:33,925
- What are you doing in my--
- It's actually a funny story.

173
00:10:33,967 --> 00:10:35,594
How did you get into my apartment?
Whoa!

174
00:10:35,636 --> 00:10:37,971
[girl] I think it's funny.
It's not like funny "ha ha."

175
00:10:38,013 --> 00:10:40,182
Or you might not think
that it's funny "ha ha."

176
00:10:40,223 --> 00:10:42,517
I think it's funny.
I guess it's all kind of relative.

177
00:10:42,559 --> 00:10:44,519
I was actually...
No, that's not...

178
00:10:44,561 --> 00:10:48,148
I made myself in the neighborhood
and now I'm here, and maybe...

179
00:10:48,190 --> 00:10:49,399
[music playing on radio]

180
00:10:51,026 --> 00:10:52,152
Okay.

181
00:10:52,194 --> 00:10:53,445
Seriously, how did you get in here?

182
00:10:53,487 --> 00:10:55,906
Are you some kind of
crazed fan or something?

183
00:10:55,947 --> 00:10:57,908
Oh, my God.
No, no, no, I recognize you.

184
00:10:57,949 --> 00:11:01,161
You did that B-grade "geek magic" thing,
didn't you? You pulled a...

185
00:11:01,203 --> 00:11:02,454
[girl] Pulled a hat
out of the rabbit.

186
00:11:02,496 --> 00:11:03,747
A hat out of the rabbit, that's right.

187
00:11:03,789 --> 00:11:04,915
[girl] I know that it didn't work.

188
00:11:04,956 --> 00:11:06,083
No, it was actually
kind of disgusting.

189
00:11:06,124 --> 00:11:07,584
[girl]
It was way worse for the rabbit.

190
00:11:07,626 --> 00:11:11,088
Well, your drop was obvious
and your body shell is flimsy.

191
00:11:11,129 --> 00:11:14,508
So if you wouldn't mind crawling out
from under my couch and...

192
00:11:14,549 --> 00:11:16,009
[slurping]

193
00:11:17,344 --> 00:11:20,806
Ta-da! Now I'm sitting
over here. Crazy!

194
00:11:20,847 --> 00:11:24,559
By the way, that rabbit thing?
That was eight years ago, okay?

195
00:11:24,601 --> 00:11:26,311
I've gotten so much
better since then.

196
00:11:26,353 --> 00:11:27,729
- Have you?
- Yeah.

197
00:11:27,771 --> 00:11:29,314
Okay, come here.
What is it that you want?

198
00:11:29,356 --> 00:11:31,024
I wanted to meet you.
Everybody, really.

199
00:11:31,066 --> 00:11:32,734
I want to be a part
of the Eye, okay?

200
00:11:32,776 --> 00:11:35,487
I said it. I do.
And I want to use my magic for good,

201
00:11:35,529 --> 00:11:39,241
like you and Merritt
and Jack especially.

202
00:11:39,282 --> 00:11:41,326
[whispers] Oh, that's right.
I know that Jack is alive.

203
00:11:41,368 --> 00:11:42,661
I know that he
faked his own death.

204
00:11:42,703 --> 00:11:45,622
I am a huge fan of faking deaths.
That was crazy!

205
00:11:45,664 --> 00:11:47,249
What is this?
A trucker's hitch?

206
00:11:47,290 --> 00:11:49,084
- Yeah.
- It's terrible.

207
00:11:49,126 --> 00:11:51,253
- Embarrassing.
- Okay.

208
00:11:51,294 --> 00:11:54,297
By the way, I am so sorry
that Henley left you.

209
00:11:54,339 --> 00:11:56,174
- Ow! God!
- [Atlas] Sorry.

210
00:11:56,216 --> 00:11:58,844
That's actually a little better.
You know what I heard?

211
00:11:58,885 --> 00:12:00,053
- What?
- About Henley?

212
00:12:00,095 --> 00:12:02,639
I heard that she got tired
of waiting around.

213
00:12:02,681 --> 00:12:05,225
She lost faith
and so she asked for an out,

214
00:12:05,267 --> 00:12:07,185
and the Eye gave it to her.

215
00:12:07,227 --> 00:12:08,520
But who knows, right?

216
00:12:08,562 --> 00:12:10,564
In matters of the heart,
so difficult to tell.

217
00:12:10,605 --> 00:12:13,108
I mean, maybe she got sick of you.
You ever think about that?

218
00:12:13,150 --> 00:12:14,526
Control issues?

219
00:12:14,568 --> 00:12:16,361
Maybe you just didn't
tie her up tight enough. Ow!

220
00:12:16,403 --> 00:12:17,821
Mmm.
Here's what's going to happen.

221
00:12:17,863 --> 00:12:20,198
You're going to stay
here and stop talking,

222
00:12:20,240 --> 00:12:21,742
and I'm going to
make a phone call,

223
00:12:21,783 --> 00:12:24,161
and in about five minutes,
some people are going...

224
00:12:26,037 --> 00:12:27,372
[cell phone vibrating]

225
00:12:30,667 --> 00:12:32,836
- [Jack] It's all in the wrist.
- [Merritt] Uh-huh.

226
00:12:32,878 --> 00:12:35,964
[Jack] Let the momentum
of the card do the work for you.

227
00:12:36,006 --> 00:12:37,174
[Merritt] Mmm-hmm.

228
00:12:37,215 --> 00:12:39,050
This last one I call the Stall.

229
00:12:41,762 --> 00:12:43,430
[whistles] Not bad.

230
00:12:43,472 --> 00:12:45,098
Now you want to see
a thing of beauty?

231
00:12:45,140 --> 00:12:46,892
- I do indeed.
- Here you go.

232
00:12:46,933 --> 00:12:49,186
And bingo bango bongo.

233
00:12:51,104 --> 00:12:53,899
That's good. No, no, no,
it's good to be positive

234
00:12:53,940 --> 00:12:55,484
despite making zero
progress in a year.

235
00:12:55,525 --> 00:12:56,610
Yeah.

236
00:12:56,651 --> 00:12:58,612
Whereas when it
comes to hypnotism,

237
00:12:58,653 --> 00:13:01,114
the student has almost
become the master.

238
00:13:01,156 --> 00:13:05,786
I like your confidence, but you might
say that you have the better teacher.

239
00:13:05,827 --> 00:13:06,953
- Ooh!
- Yeah.

240
00:13:06,995 --> 00:13:08,246
You're right.
You're right.

241
00:13:08,288 --> 00:13:10,582
Your teacher definitely doesn't
know what he's doing.

242
00:13:10,624 --> 00:13:12,584
By the way, was this
your card yesterday?

243
00:13:12,626 --> 00:13:15,045
- In fact it was.
- I thought so.

244
00:13:15,086 --> 00:13:16,671
- That's not bad.
- [vehicle approaching]

245
00:13:21,760 --> 00:13:24,179
If I can hypnotize Danny
before you hit him with a card,

246
00:13:24,221 --> 00:13:25,555
I get top bunk for a week.

247
00:13:25,597 --> 00:13:27,557
Okay, that's a deal.

248
00:13:27,599 --> 00:13:29,059
- Danny, what's up, man?
- Hey.

249
00:13:29,100 --> 00:13:31,102
Stare at the palm of your hand
and as your eyes change focus,

250
00:13:31,144 --> 00:13:32,521
you will begin to notice...

251
00:13:32,562 --> 00:13:33,605
Everything, because
I'm not hypnotized.

252
00:13:33,647 --> 00:13:36,733
It's not working.
Please don't become him.

253
00:13:36,775 --> 00:13:38,485
I didn't know you guys did party tricks

254
00:13:38,527 --> 00:13:40,237
when there weren't floozies around
to impress.

255
00:13:40,278 --> 00:13:42,572
Uh, I think we stopped
trying to impress floozies

256
00:13:42,614 --> 00:13:44,783
- in, like, 1937.
- [laughing]

257
00:13:44,825 --> 00:13:46,910
Okay, somebody broke into my apartment,
all right?

258
00:13:46,952 --> 00:13:48,745
Some amateur who knew
everything about me,

259
00:13:48,787 --> 00:13:51,373
everything about Henley leaving,
and everything about us.

260
00:13:51,414 --> 00:13:54,125
- That's her.
- Hey!

261
00:13:54,167 --> 00:13:56,461
- Hi.
- You met Lula.

262
00:13:56,503 --> 00:13:59,047
I've met her.
What is she doing here?

263
00:13:59,089 --> 00:14:04,219
I'm the new Horseman!
I'm the girl Horseman.

264
00:14:04,261 --> 00:14:05,804
Whoo!

265
00:14:05,845 --> 00:14:06,972
Yeah!

266
00:14:08,056 --> 00:14:10,600
Nobody. No excitement.
Jack? Anything?

267
00:14:10,642 --> 00:14:12,644
Dylan, tell me
what's going on here.

268
00:14:12,686 --> 00:14:17,315
Well, Lula's been on the underground
scene for the last decade,

269
00:14:17,357 --> 00:14:19,025
and I think she
has some real talent,

270
00:14:19,067 --> 00:14:21,111
and I'd like to try her on stage

271
00:14:21,152 --> 00:14:23,321
- to balance out the duo.
- What?

272
00:14:23,363 --> 00:14:24,739
No, are you serious, man?

273
00:14:24,781 --> 00:14:26,783
After Henley left, you said I could
get back on stage again.

274
00:14:26,825 --> 00:14:28,285
Not someone who just showed up.

275
00:14:28,326 --> 00:14:30,203
I told you I'd think about it,
and I have,

276
00:14:30,245 --> 00:14:32,497
and I really need you behind the scenes
with me for a little while longer.

277
00:14:32,539 --> 00:14:34,749
Dylan, come on. I've been
behind the scenes my whole life.

278
00:14:34,791 --> 00:14:38,587
Which is a crime, might I add.
Have you seen that man's face?

279
00:14:38,628 --> 00:14:42,465
Much as I appreciate the addition
of some femininity to the group,

280
00:14:42,507 --> 00:14:44,801
over and above what Atlas provides,

281
00:14:44,843 --> 00:14:47,220
I think the real issue
is we've been in this...

282
00:14:47,262 --> 00:14:49,639
Yeah, the issue is that
we have been rehearsing for months

283
00:14:49,681 --> 00:14:52,392
for something...
We don't even know what it is.

284
00:14:52,434 --> 00:14:53,852
And you're going to
keep working until...

285
00:14:53,893 --> 00:14:55,896
Until we work as a single organism.
I know, I've heard you say that.

286
00:14:55,937 --> 00:14:57,147
The thing is, when you say that,

287
00:14:57,188 --> 00:14:59,733
I think what you're
referring to is us, not you.

288
00:14:59,774 --> 00:15:02,193
Listen, I'm getting my orders
directly from the Eye.

289
00:15:02,235 --> 00:15:03,737
Okay? And then I give them to you.

290
00:15:03,778 --> 00:15:05,322
Now, if you don't like that,
you're welcome to go.

291
00:15:05,363 --> 00:15:08,116
No, I'm not going anywhere. But I'm...
Mmm. I'm taking care of myself.

292
00:15:08,158 --> 00:15:09,534
[Lula] Guys, can I just
weigh in here really quickly?

293
00:15:09,576 --> 00:15:11,077
Because I think I see
what's going on here.

294
00:15:11,119 --> 00:15:13,997
You guys are this amazing,
tight-knit family unit.

295
00:15:14,039 --> 00:15:16,416
- I'm a new person...
- We are anything but a family.

296
00:15:16,458 --> 00:15:20,503
Okay, well, my mother literally
knifed my father in the neck one time.

297
00:15:20,545 --> 00:15:22,547
So you are actually
a little bit like my family unit.

298
00:15:22,589 --> 00:15:23,882
- Literally?
- But, yeah.

299
00:15:23,923 --> 00:15:25,884
It was an accident,
I think.

300
00:15:25,926 --> 00:15:29,012
Okay. So, does this mean
we're actually going to do something?

301
00:15:29,054 --> 00:15:31,181
Yes.

302
00:15:31,222 --> 00:15:35,685
You've all heard of Octa
and their playboy CEO, Owen Case.

303
00:15:35,727 --> 00:15:38,313
His partner, Walter Mabry,
died about a year ago.

304
00:15:38,355 --> 00:15:40,106
You wanna know what all this
has been leading to?

305
00:15:40,148 --> 00:15:41,232
Yeah.

306
00:15:41,274 --> 00:15:43,693
Octa's hosting the launch
of the next-gen cell phone.

307
00:15:43,735 --> 00:15:45,236
Once these phones
hit the streets,

308
00:15:45,278 --> 00:15:48,156
they'll siphon their users'
information to the black market.

309
00:15:48,198 --> 00:15:51,910
Meaning Octa's selling privacy
to up their profit.

310
00:15:51,951 --> 00:15:54,913
So, the Eye has decided
to expose them for it.

311
00:15:54,955 --> 00:15:57,082
Our mission
is to hijack the show.

312
00:15:57,874 --> 00:15:59,834
Rehearsal's over, guys.

313
00:15:59,876 --> 00:16:01,586
This is what we've
been waiting for.

314
00:16:01,628 --> 00:16:03,129
Now it's time to get to work.

315
00:16:06,383 --> 00:16:08,343
[indistinct chatter]

316
00:16:10,261 --> 00:16:12,514
[female announcer]
<i>Welcome, Octa insiders,</i>

317
00:16:12,555 --> 00:16:14,224
<i>bloggers and journalists.</i>

318
00:16:14,265 --> 00:16:17,602
<i>We're delighted that you've joined us
to participate in our special event.</i>

319
00:16:17,644 --> 00:16:21,690
<i>Today marks the beginning of a bright
new journey in social networking.</i>

320
00:16:21,731 --> 00:16:23,400
<i>Our latest product, Octa 8...</i>

321
00:16:23,441 --> 00:16:26,236
[Jack] Keys, cell phones,
iPads, in the bin.

322
00:16:26,277 --> 00:16:28,196
Thank you, sir.

323
00:16:28,238 --> 00:16:32,742
Can't have you texting,
tweeting, recording, or eating.

324
00:16:32,784 --> 00:16:35,495
Sorry, we will take very good
care of it for you.

325
00:16:36,663 --> 00:16:38,248
Oh, by the way.

326
00:16:38,289 --> 00:16:39,999
Security memo from Case himself.

327
00:16:40,041 --> 00:16:43,545
Couple of surprise guests.
Just follow his lead, yeah?

328
00:16:43,586 --> 00:16:45,547
We're all good.
I'm heading to the control room.

329
00:16:45,588 --> 00:16:47,132
All right. Thanks, Jack.

330
00:16:47,924 --> 00:16:51,594
- Atlas, go.
- No, Dylan, I can't...

331
00:16:51,636 --> 00:16:54,014
- [Dylan] <i>What? What's the problem?</i>
- No, there's too many people...

332
00:16:54,055 --> 00:16:56,391
Atlas, I got Owen landing now.

333
00:16:56,433 --> 00:16:57,892
Okay, I'm going now.

334
00:16:57,934 --> 00:16:59,602
- Stop.
- Oh.

335
00:16:59,644 --> 00:17:00,895
[Atlas clears throat]

336
00:17:00,937 --> 00:17:02,480
- Okay.
- Thanks.

337
00:17:02,522 --> 00:17:04,858
- Pascal, we need you in the kitchen.
- [door closes]

338
00:17:04,899 --> 00:17:06,735
[indistinct announcement over PA]

339
00:17:12,198 --> 00:17:14,743
[cell phone ringing]

340
00:17:16,953 --> 00:17:17,996
[beeps]

341
00:17:23,042 --> 00:17:24,794
Look, the speech is about freedom, okay?

342
00:17:24,836 --> 00:17:26,504
That's what we're trying
to sell here, is freedom.

343
00:17:26,546 --> 00:17:27,964
Which part of that
do you not understand?

344
00:17:28,006 --> 00:17:29,466
- I know, I'm sorry.
- For goodness sake!

345
00:17:29,507 --> 00:17:32,177
Mr. Case, John from legal.
Just need your signature for release.

346
00:17:32,218 --> 00:17:33,887
Thank you so much.

347
00:17:33,928 --> 00:17:36,055
Just get it done
and get it back to me.

348
00:17:43,021 --> 00:17:44,647
- Hey there, buddy! Smile!
- [camera clicks]

349
00:17:44,689 --> 00:17:46,566
- Who are you? What the hell?
- Who am I?

350
00:17:46,608 --> 00:17:48,985
It is picture day.
Did Julie not tell you it's picture day?

351
00:17:49,027 --> 00:17:50,820
- Picture day? What are you...
- Company-wide policy.

352
00:17:50,862 --> 00:17:52,655
- Look, I got a job to do.
- I have a job to do, too.

353
00:17:52,697 --> 00:17:53,907
Hold on a second.
What is that?

354
00:17:53,948 --> 00:17:55,033
I'm going to need some backup here.

355
00:17:55,074 --> 00:17:56,242
Who are you calling?
Hey! That's my ID.

356
00:17:56,284 --> 00:17:57,410
Security, my name is--

357
00:17:57,452 --> 00:17:58,953
- Bo Walsh, thank you.
- Hey, I'm Bo Walsh!

358
00:17:58,995 --> 00:18:00,413
Not this guy.
He's not Bo Walsh.

359
00:18:00,455 --> 00:18:01,498
Calm down, please.

360
00:18:01,539 --> 00:18:03,124
Hey! Hey, what's going on?

361
00:18:03,166 --> 00:18:04,709
This guy just came and
put a flashlight in my eyes.

362
00:18:04,751 --> 00:18:07,003
I'm trying to do my job.
This guy, check his badge.

363
00:18:07,045 --> 00:18:08,713
- Who is this guy?
- I'm Bo Walsh, not him.

364
00:18:08,755 --> 00:18:10,799
It says here,
"Evans Mental Facility.

365
00:18:10,840 --> 00:18:12,300
- Mark D. Stooge."
- Hold on a second.

366
00:18:12,342 --> 00:18:13,384
I've never seen
this before in my life.

367
00:18:13,426 --> 00:18:14,677
I'm sorry, Mr. Walsh.

368
00:18:14,719 --> 00:18:16,012
- Come on, Mr. Stooge.
- Hold on. He's not Mr. Walsh!

369
00:18:16,054 --> 00:18:17,889
- Come on. Let's go.
- What's going on here?

370
00:18:17,931 --> 00:18:19,724
I'm Bo Walsh, not him!

371
00:18:19,766 --> 00:18:24,062
God, you cannot trust anybody
in this city anymore, can you?

372
00:18:24,103 --> 00:18:25,897
Get off me!
Look, I want to make a phone call.

373
00:18:25,939 --> 00:18:27,857
- I want to call my boss!
- Hey, hey! What's going on?

374
00:18:27,899 --> 00:18:29,901
I want to call my boss,
and this jackass...

375
00:18:29,943 --> 00:18:31,861
Hey! Make your phone call.
That's your right, sir.

376
00:18:31,903 --> 00:18:34,155
That's my right.

377
00:18:34,197 --> 00:18:36,074
- What the hell?
- You're crazy. Let's go.

378
00:18:36,116 --> 00:18:37,784
This isn't my...
Where's my phone?

379
00:18:37,826 --> 00:18:39,577
Where's my phone?

380
00:18:39,619 --> 00:18:41,412
Atlas, Stooge has left
the building.

381
00:18:41,454 --> 00:18:42,747
Okay.

382
00:18:42,789 --> 00:18:45,500
The circuit board is ours.
I am leaving backstage.

383
00:18:46,584 --> 00:18:48,044
[crowd cheering]

384
00:18:48,086 --> 00:18:50,213
[female announcer]
<i>Ladies and gentlemen, Owen Case.</i>

385
00:18:50,255 --> 00:18:52,882
All right. Lula, show these guys
what you're made of.

386
00:18:52,924 --> 00:18:54,300
[all applauding]

387
00:18:59,764 --> 00:19:02,642
I can take over from here.
Clark says you're on break.

388
00:19:02,684 --> 00:19:04,018
What break? Who's Clark?

389
00:19:04,060 --> 00:19:05,728
[chuckles]
"Who's Clark?" That's funny.

390
00:19:05,770 --> 00:19:08,148
Imagine if I told Roger that,
he'd freak out.

391
00:19:08,189 --> 00:19:10,149
- Don't do that!
- What?

392
00:19:10,191 --> 00:19:11,568
Who the hell is Roger?

393
00:19:11,609 --> 00:19:13,152
Does Lisa know that
you don't know Roger?

394
00:19:13,194 --> 00:19:14,529
- I don't know who Lisa is.
- Are you kidding again?

395
00:19:14,571 --> 00:19:16,573
- You don't know who Lisa is now?
- No, I don't. Just get away.

396
00:19:16,614 --> 00:19:18,825
- That is a dangerous...
- You're ruining the meat.

397
00:19:18,867 --> 00:19:20,451
Don't make me have to go to Brian!

398
00:19:20,493 --> 00:19:22,036
- I don't know who Brian is!
- Why are you acting like this?

399
00:19:22,078 --> 00:19:23,496
- I'll go straight to him.
- Give me--

400
00:19:24,539 --> 00:19:26,541
- Oh, my God!
- [screaming]

401
00:19:26,583 --> 00:19:28,334
- [people gasping]
- [glass shattering]

402
00:19:29,252 --> 00:19:30,920
[Lula] <i>What are you
doing to me?</i>

403
00:19:31,254 --> 00:19:33,381
- Help me!
- [Owen] Help her. Go!

404
00:19:33,423 --> 00:19:34,716
[Lula screaming]

405
00:19:34,757 --> 00:19:37,260
Have some water.

406
00:19:37,302 --> 00:19:40,054
I feel from your face
you're freaked by the flow of blood,

407
00:19:40,096 --> 00:19:41,764
which is fully fixable in a snap

408
00:19:41,806 --> 00:19:45,351
by focusing and following
the flow of my words

409
00:19:45,393 --> 00:19:47,729
as you're flowing and floating,

410
00:19:47,770 --> 00:19:50,732
which is why you're focusing
on my commands.

411
00:19:50,773 --> 00:19:52,191
[echoing]
You got this far in life

412
00:19:52,233 --> 00:19:54,903
by listening to one voice,
the voice in your head.

413
00:19:54,944 --> 00:19:56,863
This is that voice.

414
00:19:56,905 --> 00:19:58,072
[door closes]

415
00:19:59,240 --> 00:20:00,742
Look at the light.

416
00:20:00,783 --> 00:20:03,661
Listen to your own voice.

417
00:20:03,703 --> 00:20:05,538
[video camera beeping]

418
00:20:07,999 --> 00:20:10,501
Oh, my God.
[groaning]

419
00:20:13,338 --> 00:20:16,216
Wow. What is that?
Is that a miracle towel?

420
00:20:16,257 --> 00:20:17,967
Thank you so much.
Do you know what?

421
00:20:18,009 --> 00:20:21,471
You have taught me that I'm not
cut out for this kind of work.

422
00:20:21,512 --> 00:20:23,181
I quit!

423
00:20:23,223 --> 00:20:24,974
Get another towel.

424
00:20:25,391 --> 00:20:27,393
Thank you, and goodbye.

425
00:20:27,435 --> 00:20:29,437
- [people gasping]
- Oh, God.

426
00:20:31,564 --> 00:20:33,816
[female announcer]
Welcome everybody!

427
00:20:33,858 --> 00:20:36,819
And now, the moment
that you've all been waiting for...

428
00:20:37,987 --> 00:20:39,989
- Nice work, lady.
- Thanks.

429
00:20:40,031 --> 00:20:43,117
[announcer]
Revolutionized music with Octa 2.

430
00:20:44,869 --> 00:20:47,789
I'm actually nervous,
and I'm not even going onstage.

431
00:20:47,830 --> 00:20:50,083
You know, I've heard
that if you're nervous,

432
00:20:50,124 --> 00:20:53,169
it can be really helpful
to picture each other naked.

433
00:20:53,211 --> 00:20:55,004
It's actually picture
the audience naked.

434
00:20:55,046 --> 00:20:56,756
No, this is new.
This is a new science.

435
00:20:56,798 --> 00:20:58,174
So, I don't know.

436
00:20:58,216 --> 00:21:01,427
- Do you want... We should try it.
- Not the right mood.

437
00:21:01,469 --> 00:21:03,137
Guess that leaves
you and me, old buddy.

438
00:21:03,179 --> 00:21:06,015
What? Picture each other...
No. No, thank you.

439
00:21:06,641 --> 00:21:09,060
I mean, I admit,
from the neck up there are issues.

440
00:21:09,102 --> 00:21:12,230
But from the neck down, the David.

441
00:21:12,272 --> 00:21:13,773
Owen Case.

442
00:21:13,815 --> 00:21:15,733
[all cheering]

443
00:21:15,775 --> 00:21:19,195
Good morning, Octa-lites.

444
00:21:20,238 --> 00:21:21,781
Now, I've made the claim...

445
00:21:21,823 --> 00:21:24,617
<i>Now, I've made the claim
that Octa 8 is pure magic.</i>

446
00:21:24,659 --> 00:21:27,704
But the truth is, that's just
one of those things I say...

447
00:21:27,745 --> 00:21:31,207
<i>You know, the truth is,
that's just one of those things I say...</i>

448
00:21:31,249 --> 00:21:33,543
...when in fact
I mean something else.

449
00:21:33,584 --> 00:21:37,797
<i>...when in fact
I mean something else.</i>

450
00:21:37,839 --> 00:21:39,173
What else do I mean?

451
00:21:39,215 --> 00:21:45,513
<i>Well, here to fill you in on some of my
fabulous lies and hypocrisy,</i>

452
00:21:45,555 --> 00:21:49,559
<i>and to perform some of the most dazzling
feats of magic you have ever seen...</i>

453
00:21:49,600 --> 00:21:52,228
- They are the world's...
<i>- ...greatest magicians.</i>

454
00:21:52,270 --> 00:21:55,064
<i>Here to expose me
for the fraud I truly am.</i>

455
00:21:55,106 --> 00:21:59,485
<i>Ladies and gentlemen,
here are the Horsemen.</i>

456
00:22:01,738 --> 00:22:03,072
[audience gasping]

457
00:22:06,617 --> 00:22:08,202
[all cheering]

458
00:22:08,244 --> 00:22:09,871
[cameras clicking]

459
00:22:13,291 --> 00:22:15,084
[Atlas] Hello, New York!

460
00:22:15,168 --> 00:22:17,086
Thank you so much.

461
00:22:17,128 --> 00:22:18,921
Hey, it's great to be back.

462
00:22:18,963 --> 00:22:22,300
[Atlas] And have you met
our newest Horseman, Lula?

463
00:22:25,470 --> 00:22:29,349
- Feels good, right?
- Pretty good. Pretty good.

464
00:22:31,642 --> 00:22:33,561
[Atlas]
Thank you, thank you. Um, okay.

465
00:22:33,603 --> 00:22:35,396
We want to talk to you
about your privacy.

466
00:22:35,438 --> 00:22:37,482
What does your privacy mean to you?

467
00:22:37,523 --> 00:22:40,318
Because apparently to Owen Case,
it means absolutely nothing.

468
00:22:40,360 --> 00:22:42,862
No, actually it means less
than absolutely nothing.

469
00:22:42,904 --> 00:22:45,990
You see, he's mocked your privacy.
He's scorned it.

470
00:22:46,032 --> 00:22:49,077
Right, and we're not just talking about
the things that you already agreed to

471
00:22:49,118 --> 00:22:51,370
when you signed,
probably without reading

472
00:22:51,412 --> 00:22:54,624
the terms and conditions
of Octas 1 through 7.

473
00:22:58,336 --> 00:23:01,214
Dylan, the FBI is here.

474
00:23:01,255 --> 00:23:03,591
All right. Don't worry about it.

475
00:23:03,633 --> 00:23:05,676
All right, go to plan C-4.

476
00:23:06,928 --> 00:23:08,805
Lock the doors.

477
00:23:08,846 --> 00:23:10,473
Hey, boss, I'm glad you're here.

478
00:23:10,515 --> 00:23:11,974
Don't.

479
00:23:12,475 --> 00:23:15,144
[Dylan] Guys, look. We got to move
around, get in through the back.

480
00:23:15,186 --> 00:23:16,521
These Horsemen are tricky, okay?

481
00:23:16,562 --> 00:23:19,690
They got backup plans
on top of backup plans.

482
00:23:19,732 --> 00:23:21,818
Hey, sorry, don't mean to gloat,
but I told you so.

483
00:23:21,859 --> 00:23:23,069
Cut the bullshit, Rhodes.

484
00:23:23,111 --> 00:23:25,321
We got an anonymous
phone call an hour ago.

485
00:23:25,363 --> 00:23:27,073
Confirms everything
I've been telling her.

486
00:23:27,115 --> 00:23:28,157
What are you talking about?

487
00:23:28,199 --> 00:23:29,575
You sent agents
to Detroit and Philadelphia.

488
00:23:29,617 --> 00:23:31,911
You've been crying wolf
so we wouldn't send them here.

489
00:23:31,953 --> 00:23:34,622
- Boss, please.
- Keep working on the doors.

490
00:23:34,664 --> 00:23:38,626
Please tell me that you haven't bought
into Cowan's crazy, paranoid fantasia.

491
00:23:38,668 --> 00:23:40,294
[Lula] Before we start the show...

492
00:23:40,336 --> 00:23:44,090
We had Owen agree to a few terms
and conditions of our own.

493
00:23:44,132 --> 00:23:47,176
So, everything that he had
once considered private...

494
00:23:47,218 --> 00:23:48,594
- [static]
- [audience booing]

495
00:23:48,636 --> 00:23:51,806
That he thinks is really private...

496
00:23:51,848 --> 00:23:55,852
Yeah, everything that he once
considered private is now...

497
00:23:55,893 --> 00:23:57,270
- [devices powering down]
- Oh, my.

498
00:23:59,522 --> 00:24:01,190
[high-pitched static]

499
00:24:01,232 --> 00:24:06,070
<i>As the Horsemen like to say,
magic is about controlling perception.</i>

500
00:24:06,112 --> 00:24:10,199
<i>You see them as champions of the truth,
but are they?</i>

501
00:24:10,241 --> 00:24:13,202
<i>Or is that just another
one of their illusions?</i>

502
00:24:13,244 --> 00:24:15,830
- What's going on, Rhodes?
- [stammers] This is crazy.

503
00:24:15,872 --> 00:24:17,373
We got to get everyone
to the other exits.

504
00:24:17,415 --> 00:24:20,042
- Let's go, to the back.
- No. You stay here.

505
00:24:20,084 --> 00:24:22,336
<i>So, since they clearly
love secrets...</i>

506
00:24:22,378 --> 00:24:24,922
<i>Let's reveal some of theirs.</i>

507
00:24:24,964 --> 00:24:26,716
Danny, everyone, get off the stage.

508
00:24:26,757 --> 00:24:28,843
<i>- Abort.</i>
- [all screaming]

509
00:24:28,885 --> 00:24:31,596
Jack, go with them.
I'll see you at the meet-up point.

510
00:24:31,637 --> 00:24:32,680
[Atlas] Let's go.

511
00:24:32,722 --> 00:24:34,891
[man on video]
<i>Do you recall the death of Jack Wilder?</i>

512
00:24:34,932 --> 00:24:40,396
<i>What if I told you he's not just alive,
but he's actually right here.</i>

513
00:24:41,397 --> 00:24:42,648
[crowd gasping]

514
00:24:42,690 --> 00:24:44,066
[cameras clicking]

515
00:24:46,903 --> 00:24:50,239
<i>And do you know who else is here?
The FBI.</i>

516
00:24:50,281 --> 00:24:52,533
<i>Let's let them in, shall we?</i>

517
00:24:52,575 --> 00:24:53,910
[doors unlocking]

518
00:24:53,951 --> 00:24:55,745
<i>And now, for the big reveal.</i>

519
00:24:55,786 --> 00:24:58,498
[Austin]
Go! Go! To the stage.

520
00:24:58,539 --> 00:25:00,625
<i>There's a fifth Horseman,</i>

521
00:25:00,666 --> 00:25:03,503
<i>and he's the biggest
criminal of them all.</i>

522
00:25:03,544 --> 00:25:06,214
<i>FBI agent, Dylan Rhodes.</i>

523
00:25:06,255 --> 00:25:07,715
[audience exclaiming]

524
00:25:07,757 --> 00:25:09,467
- [Cowan] I knew it.
- [Austin] What?

525
00:25:10,927 --> 00:25:12,595
This is so much deeper
than you know, boss.

526
00:25:12,637 --> 00:25:14,847
You think you're looking at one thing,
but you have no idea.

527
00:25:14,889 --> 00:25:17,350
- Who are you?
- The same man I've always been.

528
00:25:17,391 --> 00:25:19,185
- Boys, I'm sorry.
- [handcuffs clattering]

529
00:25:20,853 --> 00:25:22,313
[handcuffs clicking]

530
00:25:27,818 --> 00:25:29,570
[Cowan]
You gotta be kidding me.

531
00:25:29,612 --> 00:25:31,697
[Jack]
We've gotta get to the chute. Go!

532
00:25:31,739 --> 00:25:34,534
- [Lula] Who are those guys?
- [Jack] Who cares? Come on!

533
00:25:34,575 --> 00:25:35,785
- Hurry, hurry!
- Keep going!

534
00:25:35,826 --> 00:25:36,869
How the hell could this happen?

535
00:25:36,911 --> 00:25:38,621
I thought Dylan
had everything under control.

536
00:25:38,663 --> 00:25:40,498
Yeah. Apparently he didn't.

537
00:25:40,540 --> 00:25:43,626
Maybe you're the leak, Dan.
Where you been sneaking off to?

538
00:25:43,668 --> 00:25:45,211
Don't you dare for a second
insinuate that I had...

539
00:25:45,253 --> 00:25:48,673
- I'm not insinuating. That's your...
- Let's get to the truck, come on!

540
00:25:48,714 --> 00:25:50,925
- Stay together!
- Move! Move!

541
00:25:50,967 --> 00:25:52,051
Lula, come on!

542
00:25:52,093 --> 00:25:54,053
Coming! Whoa!

543
00:25:54,095 --> 00:25:55,972
[all screaming]

544
00:25:56,973 --> 00:25:58,099
Whoa, whoa, whoa!

545
00:26:01,227 --> 00:26:02,603
[screaming robotically]

546
00:26:02,645 --> 00:26:06,357
[man]
<i>Sleep. Sleep. Sleep. Sleep.</i>

547
00:26:07,441 --> 00:26:09,026
[all groaning]

548
00:26:09,068 --> 00:26:10,820
[Lula screaming]

549
00:26:10,861 --> 00:26:12,488
[indistinct chatter]

550
00:26:16,826 --> 00:26:18,327
What the hell is going on?

551
00:26:18,369 --> 00:26:20,705
- Wasn't there supposed to be a truck?
- Where the hell are we?

552
00:26:20,746 --> 00:26:22,873
[shouting in Cantonese]

553
00:26:22,915 --> 00:26:24,208
Come on!

554
00:26:24,250 --> 00:26:26,168
Hey, hey!
Wait, did you mis-run the tube?

555
00:26:26,210 --> 00:26:27,878
No, I put it in the truck.
I know I did!

556
00:26:27,920 --> 00:26:29,505
[Atlas] Because we're really
not in the truck right now.

557
00:26:29,547 --> 00:26:30,923
[Merritt] Somebody must
have moved the tube.

558
00:26:30,965 --> 00:26:32,466
Were we above a Chinese restaurant?
Give me that!

559
00:26:32,508 --> 00:26:34,594
- [Jack] I'm moving! Relax!
- [Lula] There's something very wrong.

560
00:26:37,430 --> 00:26:39,682
Okay. Why are we here?

561
00:26:39,724 --> 00:26:41,726
Why am I frickin' starving?

562
00:26:41,767 --> 00:26:43,936
[Jack]
Yeah, I'm weirdly starving, too.

563
00:26:43,978 --> 00:26:46,272
This makes no sense.

564
00:26:49,066 --> 00:26:50,276
[horn honking]

565
00:27:10,212 --> 00:27:11,589
Okay, sorry.

566
00:27:12,840 --> 00:27:15,259
At least, and I know this
isn't much consolation,

567
00:27:15,301 --> 00:27:18,054
but apparently
we're now surrounded by Chinese food.

568
00:27:18,095 --> 00:27:20,389
- Right?
- Guys...

569
00:27:20,431 --> 00:27:24,060
I think where we are right now, they
don't refer to it as "Chinese food."

570
00:27:24,101 --> 00:27:26,854
It's just called "food."

571
00:27:31,067 --> 00:27:33,819
Wait, what are you saying?
How is this possible?

572
00:27:33,861 --> 00:27:36,113
[laughing]

573
00:27:36,155 --> 00:27:41,661
I believe in your particular parlance,
the word is "magic."

574
00:27:41,702 --> 00:27:44,246
That guy looks exactly like you.

575
00:27:44,288 --> 00:27:47,375
He looks exactly like you.
Are you seeing this right now?

576
00:27:47,416 --> 00:27:48,584
Chase.

577
00:27:48,626 --> 00:27:52,630
Must confess, it's like what I heard
about meeting the Rolling Stones.

578
00:27:52,671 --> 00:27:54,632
They're a lot shorter in person.

579
00:27:54,673 --> 00:27:57,551
Remember I told you about the guy
who screwed me out of everything?

580
00:27:57,593 --> 00:28:00,930
This is my twin brother, Chase.

581
00:28:01,055 --> 00:28:02,807
Wait, did you do this?

582
00:28:02,848 --> 00:28:05,059
- [men shouting]
- [guns cocking]

583
00:28:05,101 --> 00:28:08,938
[Chase chuckles] As you can see,
my boss don't mess around.

584
00:28:08,979 --> 00:28:11,690
I do not understand what is
going on right now. At all.

585
00:28:11,732 --> 00:28:13,859
Okay, let me break it
down for you.

586
00:28:13,901 --> 00:28:17,947
You jumped off a rooftop in New York
and you landed in Macau.

587
00:28:17,988 --> 00:28:21,575
AKA the Vegas of China.

588
00:28:21,617 --> 00:28:23,953
And presto-changeo.

589
00:28:23,994 --> 00:28:25,204
Don't you just love it?

590
00:28:25,246 --> 00:28:27,373
The "greatest magicians in the world"

591
00:28:27,415 --> 00:28:29,917
are the object
of someone else's magic trick?

592
00:28:29,959 --> 00:28:32,169
Isn't that poetic?

593
00:28:33,546 --> 00:28:37,842
No? [stammers] You know what,
I'm not gonna let you guys yuck my yum.

594
00:28:37,883 --> 00:28:40,344
Shoo-shoo. Or mu-shu. Whatever.

595
00:28:40,386 --> 00:28:41,637
[men clamoring]

596
00:28:41,679 --> 00:28:46,434
Oh, and you know what they say,
"What happens in Macau..."

597
00:28:46,475 --> 00:28:49,770
Uh, well, I don't know the rest of it,
'cause it's in Chinese, uh...

598
00:28:49,812 --> 00:28:51,564
Hey, thanks, guys!

599
00:28:54,775 --> 00:28:56,485
[indistinct shouting]

600
00:29:11,041 --> 00:29:13,502
<i>Reports are coming in
that the infamous Horsemen</i>

601
00:29:13,544 --> 00:29:15,671
<i>hijacked the Octa product launch today.</i>

602
00:29:15,713 --> 00:29:17,381
<i>The trick was on them, however,</i>

603
00:29:17,423 --> 00:29:20,801
<i>as we learned of the miraculous
resurrection of Jack Wilder.</i>

604
00:29:20,843 --> 00:29:23,929
<i>And the stunning revelation
that FBI Agent Dylan Rhodes</i>

605
00:29:23,971 --> 00:29:26,432
<i>has been working as a mole
within the Bureau.</i>

606
00:29:26,474 --> 00:29:29,894
<i>Questions abound today as an
international manhunt is underway</i>

607
00:29:29,935 --> 00:29:33,689
<i>for Dylan Rhodes and his elusive
and criminal band of illusionists.</i>

608
00:29:33,731 --> 00:29:35,107
[voicemail beeps]

609
00:29:35,149 --> 00:29:37,443
Hey, seriously, where are you guys?

610
00:29:37,485 --> 00:29:39,361
I'm at the meetup.
I've been leaving you messages.

611
00:29:39,403 --> 00:29:41,781
I haven't heard from anyone.
Please, call me!

612
00:29:41,822 --> 00:29:42,990
[male news anchor]
<i>And the stock market</i>

613
00:29:43,032 --> 00:29:45,785
<i>saw big gains and modest
losses on Thursday.</i>

614
00:29:45,826 --> 00:29:47,161
[ringing]

615
00:29:47,203 --> 00:29:48,829
Hey, tell me you're safe.
Where are you?

616
00:29:48,871 --> 00:29:53,250
[Thaddeus] Right where you left me,
18 months ago, Agent Rhodes.

617
00:29:53,292 --> 00:29:54,502
Thaddeus?

618
00:29:54,543 --> 00:29:56,462
<i>How does it feel
to lose everything?</i>

619
00:29:56,504 --> 00:30:00,466
Your job. Your identity.
Your reason for living.

620
00:30:00,508 --> 00:30:03,677
How does it feel to be out of control,
perhaps for the first time?

621
00:30:06,138 --> 00:30:07,264
What do you want?

622
00:30:07,306 --> 00:30:10,351
You're a fool, Agent Rhodes.
You always have been.

623
00:30:11,185 --> 00:30:13,437
- Where are they?
- I'm not telling you on the phone!

624
00:30:13,479 --> 00:30:14,522
Where are they?

625
00:30:14,563 --> 00:30:18,609
And if you're wondering if I was behind
the Horsemen's recent debacle,

626
00:30:18,651 --> 00:30:20,444
I'll let you work
that out for yourself.

627
00:30:20,486 --> 00:30:23,531
Hey, I burned you once, I'll burn
you again. I'm not playing, Thaddeus.

628
00:30:23,572 --> 00:30:26,283
It's not my game,
Agent Rhodes. It's yours.

629
00:30:26,325 --> 00:30:28,827
You started it when
you locked me in a cell.

630
00:30:28,869 --> 00:30:30,621
<i>This is simply my move.</i>

631
00:30:30,663 --> 00:30:32,665
Next one is yours.

632
00:30:35,960 --> 00:30:37,336
[Young Dylan] <i>No!</i>

633
00:30:38,128 --> 00:30:39,713
Let go!

634
00:30:40,506 --> 00:30:44,009
Dad! Help me! Dad!

635
00:30:45,135 --> 00:30:46,762
<i>Dad!</i>

636
00:30:47,513 --> 00:30:48,639
[tires screeching]

637
00:31:04,154 --> 00:31:06,115
[Chase]
It's all about blind spots.

638
00:31:06,156 --> 00:31:11,036
When you're staring straight
at something, and not see it. Why?

639
00:31:11,745 --> 00:31:13,497
Blind spots.

640
00:31:13,539 --> 00:31:15,791
We learned that together,
didn't we, bro?

641
00:31:15,833 --> 00:31:18,711
Did he tell you that
we were partners once?

642
00:31:18,752 --> 00:31:21,964
No? I didn't think so.
The "Mini-McKinneys."

643
00:31:22,006 --> 00:31:24,383
<i>♪ Chasey and a Mer-Bear</i>

644
00:31:24,425 --> 00:31:26,468
<i>♪ Gonna make you scare-bear</i>

645
00:31:26,510 --> 00:31:29,889
<i>♪ Ma-ma-magic McKinneys ♪</i>

646
00:31:29,930 --> 00:31:31,974
- [groans]
- [Lula] Cool.

647
00:31:32,016 --> 00:31:38,647
And then, one day, we were 12
and Virginia Von Welsheim

648
00:31:38,689 --> 00:31:41,609
had a very nice party
down the street.

649
00:31:41,650 --> 00:31:43,986
I had a little tum-tum, couldn't go.

650
00:31:44,028 --> 00:31:49,617
Mer-Bear did it on his own, and got
a taste of the solo thing, and uh...

651
00:31:51,493 --> 00:31:54,288
- ...and kicked me to the curb.
- Oh, God.

652
00:31:54,330 --> 00:31:58,834
Chase, you win! I concede.
Just tell me how you did it.

653
00:31:58,876 --> 00:32:05,090
Delivery guy came to your door
about a month ago, little za.

654
00:32:05,215 --> 00:32:06,258
Za?

655
00:32:06,300 --> 00:32:09,261
- Pizza, huh?
- [doorbell ringing]

656
00:32:09,303 --> 00:32:13,682
- Is this apartment d3375?
- Not even close.

657
00:32:17,811 --> 00:32:19,271
Sleep!

658
00:32:19,480 --> 00:32:22,941
Relaxing, floating,
drifting, dreaming...

659
00:32:22,983 --> 00:32:25,027
- [thuds]
- Falling.

660
00:32:25,069 --> 00:32:27,696
So, what he did,
my little womb-mate,

661
00:32:27,738 --> 00:32:31,700
is he downloaded all
your private information,

662
00:32:31,742 --> 00:32:34,954
and my employer
had all he needed.

663
00:32:34,995 --> 00:32:36,413
Thanks.

664
00:32:36,455 --> 00:32:39,291
How did you know how to find him?

665
00:32:39,333 --> 00:32:42,544
- That's a very good question, Atlas.
- Okay.

666
00:32:59,812 --> 00:33:03,607
[Chase] Just follow the guards.
They'll take you to my boss.

667
00:33:06,986 --> 00:33:10,781
Been fun playing this cat-and-mouse
with you, broski.

668
00:33:10,823 --> 00:33:12,700
Meow.

669
00:33:12,741 --> 00:33:14,284
[chase laughing]

670
00:33:14,326 --> 00:33:17,121
Have fun at the Sands.

671
00:33:17,162 --> 00:33:18,998
[people cheering]

672
00:33:20,499 --> 00:33:23,460
- I am so, so, so sorry.
- Yeah, you should be.

673
00:33:23,502 --> 00:33:26,714
Don't ever accuse me
of betraying us again, okay?

674
00:33:39,101 --> 00:33:41,854
Do you guys ever think that
the Eye is watching this?

675
00:33:41,895 --> 00:33:44,398
You know, that maybe this
is even what they want?

676
00:33:46,483 --> 00:33:48,110
And at the exact right moment,

677
00:33:48,152 --> 00:33:50,446
they're gonna swoop in,
and we'll be like,

678
00:33:50,487 --> 00:33:52,364
"Yes! Thank God you're here!

679
00:33:52,406 --> 00:33:54,908
Thank God!
Just in the nick of time, Eye!"

680
00:33:54,950 --> 00:33:58,996
And then we'll just celebrate,
and it was all worth it in the end?

681
00:34:03,167 --> 00:34:05,252
I don't even really
think that, either, so...

682
00:34:05,294 --> 00:34:07,254
- It's cool.
- [elevator dings]

683
00:34:07,296 --> 00:34:09,006
[doors open]

684
00:34:09,048 --> 00:34:10,966
[rock music playing]

685
00:34:21,560 --> 00:34:22,686
Ah.

686
00:34:23,604 --> 00:34:24,646
Ta-da!

687
00:34:26,231 --> 00:34:28,358
So happy to be working with you.

688
00:34:28,400 --> 00:34:30,068
- [music stops]
- Please, come in. Come in.

689
00:34:30,110 --> 00:34:32,279
Whoa, whoa, whoa.

690
00:34:32,321 --> 00:34:33,697
Wait, sorry, how are you
working with us?

691
00:34:33,739 --> 00:34:36,700
Oh, well, as much as a magician
who pulls a rabbit from a hat

692
00:34:36,742 --> 00:34:39,620
is working with that rabbit.

693
00:34:39,661 --> 00:34:43,248
We'll be working together. Yes.
Allow me to introduce myself.

694
00:34:43,290 --> 00:34:45,834
Yeah, you're Walter Mabry.
You died a year ago.

695
00:34:45,876 --> 00:34:47,795
Yes. An idea I got
from you, Mr. Wilder.

696
00:34:47,836 --> 00:34:49,797
Fake your death,
the world puts its guard down.

697
00:34:49,838 --> 00:34:51,882
I'm able to control
quite a few companies,

698
00:34:51,924 --> 00:34:53,467
including my old partner, Owen's,

699
00:34:53,509 --> 00:34:56,678
as a consortium of so-called
anonymous shareholders.

700
00:34:56,720 --> 00:35:00,474
- And that violates how many SEC laws?
- I believe it breaks all of them.

701
00:35:00,516 --> 00:35:01,934
[gasps] All of them.

702
00:35:01,975 --> 00:35:04,895
You see, you all want an audience.

703
00:35:04,937 --> 00:35:08,398
Need one, desperately.
It's quite sad, really.

704
00:35:08,440 --> 00:35:10,567
Hence, my ability to nab you.

705
00:35:10,609 --> 00:35:13,445
I, on the other hand,
want the opposite of that.

706
00:35:13,487 --> 00:35:17,908
I just want to be, and I am
100 percent off the grid.

707
00:35:17,950 --> 00:35:19,284
You know why?

708
00:35:19,326 --> 00:35:21,870
Yeah, because the grid
is for actual human beings.

709
00:35:21,912 --> 00:35:24,289
No, because in a world
of total surveillance,

710
00:35:24,331 --> 00:35:27,501
the only true freedom
lies in not being seen.

711
00:35:27,543 --> 00:35:29,837
You can't control the grid
from within the grid.

712
00:35:29,878 --> 00:35:31,797
- Follow me.
- Yeah.

713
00:35:31,839 --> 00:35:33,674
- Follow me.
- Okay. All right.

714
00:35:33,715 --> 00:35:36,051
You pulled a hat out of a rabbit.
That was very colorful.

715
00:35:36,093 --> 00:35:39,638
Almost eight and a half years ago.
So, no need to bring that up.

716
00:35:39,680 --> 00:35:42,349
We can't all be held accountable
for our adolescent personas.

717
00:35:42,391 --> 00:35:44,560
Can we, Magicolio?

718
00:35:44,601 --> 00:35:46,979
Magicolio, that was 15 years ago.

719
00:35:47,020 --> 00:35:48,939
Don't get me wrong, I love magic.

720
00:35:48,981 --> 00:35:50,190
Like you, and many others who,

721
00:35:50,232 --> 00:35:53,318
I suppose, were not getting any sex
in high school, I dabbled with it.

722
00:35:53,360 --> 00:35:58,782
But, uh, unlike you, I was able to
transition upward towards actual magic.

723
00:35:58,824 --> 00:36:00,993
Science, you may
have heard it called.

724
00:36:03,495 --> 00:36:07,875
So, would you like to know,
my friends, just how I got you here?

725
00:36:07,916 --> 00:36:09,293
We know how you did it.

726
00:36:09,334 --> 00:36:10,377
No, you don't.

727
00:36:10,419 --> 00:36:13,171
Yeah, you stole our files for the show,
then obviously hypnotized us.

728
00:36:13,213 --> 00:36:14,673
Stop. No. Seriously, stop.

729
00:36:14,715 --> 00:36:17,092
The strobe was a combo
of binaural beats, as well as--

730
00:36:17,134 --> 00:36:19,511
I said stop!

731
00:36:19,553 --> 00:36:22,097
You might not be having fun,
but I am.

732
00:36:22,848 --> 00:36:25,309
You have an unusual way of showing it.

733
00:36:25,934 --> 00:36:26,977
So...

734
00:36:27,728 --> 00:36:29,605
How did I do it?

735
00:36:29,646 --> 00:36:34,234
Easy. You see, magicians like to control
other people's perceptions.

736
00:36:34,276 --> 00:36:35,611
In your heightened state of agitation,

737
00:36:35,652 --> 00:36:38,030
<i>you saw the simplest cues.
Black tube, roof.</i>

738
00:36:38,071 --> 00:36:40,532
<i>And your minds filled in the rest.</i>

739
00:36:40,574 --> 00:36:43,452
<i>But the tube you meant to go down
was 20 feet to your right.</i>

740
00:36:43,493 --> 00:36:45,537
Go on, sit down. There's no one
standing in your way.

741
00:36:45,579 --> 00:36:47,080
Don't mind if I do.

742
00:36:48,916 --> 00:36:51,126
Anyway, once in the tube,
yes, you're right...

743
00:36:51,168 --> 00:36:55,005
<i>Blah, blah, blah, the strobe contained
UV letters pulsing the word "sleep."</i>

744
00:36:57,049 --> 00:37:00,886
<i>And that, combined with the sound,
put you into an instant alpha pattern.</i>

745
00:37:00,928 --> 00:37:03,764
<i>Sleep, sleep, sleep.</i>

746
00:37:03,805 --> 00:37:05,515
And from then on,
it really was just fun.

747
00:37:05,557 --> 00:37:08,977
And I can assure you,
you don't know what happened.

748
00:37:09,019 --> 00:37:10,437
[slow music playing on video]

749
00:37:13,649 --> 00:37:16,693
That's really creepy.
Really, really creepy.

750
00:37:19,321 --> 00:37:20,781
[Merritt] That's not cool.

751
00:37:20,822 --> 00:37:22,991
[Walter]
Yep, easy stuff, magic,

752
00:37:23,700 --> 00:37:25,118
if you put your mind to it.

753
00:37:25,160 --> 00:37:27,162
All right, that's enough.
So why are we here, then?

754
00:37:27,204 --> 00:37:29,957
Besides you getting to show off
how adorably clever you are.

755
00:37:29,998 --> 00:37:32,834
Well, to start with,
the man you stole from last year,

756
00:37:32,876 --> 00:37:35,671
turns out I had invested quite a lot
of money in some of his companies,

757
00:37:35,712 --> 00:37:38,966
so a lot of what you
stole was, in fact, mine.

758
00:37:39,007 --> 00:37:41,802
Good news is, it's very easy for you
to pay me back.

759
00:37:41,843 --> 00:37:44,596
I just need your skills.

760
00:37:44,638 --> 00:37:47,557
Owen and I were like the Beatles,
if the Beatles had been...

761
00:37:47,599 --> 00:37:48,684
Elfin?

762
00:37:48,725 --> 00:37:50,102
...geniuses.

763
00:37:50,143 --> 00:37:51,812
Pretty sure the Beatles were geniuses.

764
00:37:51,853 --> 00:37:54,189
And like them, we had a dream.

765
00:37:55,023 --> 00:37:58,777
Could we create actual, genuine magic?

766
00:37:58,819 --> 00:38:02,239
And I'm guessing one of you achieved
that dream, and it wasn't you?

767
00:38:02,280 --> 00:38:05,450
That is what he
would like you to think.

768
00:38:05,492 --> 00:38:10,622
My vision was a perfect blend
of elegance and technology.

769
00:38:10,664 --> 00:38:13,041
But Owen wanted it for himself
so he humiliated me

770
00:38:13,083 --> 00:38:16,295
by exposing my private files
to the board of directors

771
00:38:16,336 --> 00:38:17,796
and convinced them
that I am unstable.

772
00:38:17,838 --> 00:38:20,048
Did you take a picture of him
while he was sleeping?

773
00:38:20,090 --> 00:38:21,466
He had me kicked out of
my own company,

774
00:38:21,508 --> 00:38:23,927
and now he goes around
taking credit for a chip

775
00:38:23,969 --> 00:38:25,762
that's not just the key to one computer,

776
00:38:25,804 --> 00:38:28,849
but every computer
system on the planet.

777
00:38:28,890 --> 00:38:32,019
It can un-encrypt anything,
crack the defense firewall,

778
00:38:32,060 --> 00:38:34,855
manipulate markets,
and spy on anyone.

779
00:38:34,896 --> 00:38:36,690
And now it's being sold
to the highest bidder.

780
00:38:36,732 --> 00:38:38,400
If you're so rich,
why don't you just buy it?

781
00:38:38,442 --> 00:38:39,901
So he gets the money?

782
00:38:39,943 --> 00:38:42,154
And the pleasure? No.

783
00:38:42,195 --> 00:38:45,490
No, no, no. Besides, why would I buy it
when I could have you steal it for me?

784
00:38:45,532 --> 00:38:46,742
Oh!

785
00:38:46,783 --> 00:38:48,744
It's being previewed tomorrow
to the various suitors,

786
00:38:48,785 --> 00:38:52,497
which will include your targets,
a crew lead by a South African gangster.

787
00:38:52,539 --> 00:38:54,041
South African gangster.

788
00:38:54,082 --> 00:38:55,834
Yes. How your team
gets past security, that's up to you.

789
00:38:55,876 --> 00:38:59,171
But once you do, you just need
to inspect it and steal it.

790
00:38:59,212 --> 00:39:00,255
That's it?

791
00:39:00,297 --> 00:39:02,132
Come on, this is
perfect for you, isn't it?

792
00:39:02,174 --> 00:39:03,300
You're magicians and thieves.

793
00:39:03,342 --> 00:39:05,969
What makes you think we would even
consider doing this?

794
00:39:06,011 --> 00:39:09,389
Um, oh, wait, I had a reason.
What was it? Oh, yes.

795
00:39:09,431 --> 00:39:11,058
You see, back home,
you're wanted criminals.

796
00:39:11,099 --> 00:39:14,394
But here, I control the police,
the casinos, the media.

797
00:39:14,436 --> 00:39:17,689
I can give you a new life,
out of hiding.

798
00:39:18,523 --> 00:39:21,151
And if you don't,
I'll have you killed.

799
00:39:23,153 --> 00:39:25,822
You know what?
I'm not stealing a thing for you.

800
00:39:25,864 --> 00:39:29,993
- Not unless Dylan tells me it's okay.
- Really? Dylan is where, exactly?

801
00:39:30,035 --> 00:39:32,954
It doesn't matter. Yeah, I'm with him.
So you can go ahead and kill us

802
00:39:32,996 --> 00:39:35,040
because I'm not gonna
steal anything for you either.

803
00:39:35,082 --> 00:39:38,710
[Merritt] Strikes me that a consensus
seems to be forming, Walter,

804
00:39:38,752 --> 00:39:40,337
and we're calling your bluff.

805
00:39:42,005 --> 00:39:44,091
- [Atlas] Actually, we'll do it.
- [both] What?

806
00:39:44,132 --> 00:39:46,927
We're in Macau. The oldest
magic store in the world is here.

807
00:39:46,968 --> 00:39:50,347
We'll get the supplies
we need, and we'll do it.

808
00:39:50,972 --> 00:39:52,891
Thank you.

809
00:39:52,933 --> 00:39:54,434
It should be fun.

810
00:39:54,476 --> 00:39:57,521
Chase will take you
to the magic shop in the morning.

811
00:40:02,609 --> 00:40:03,652
[guard] Badge.

812
00:40:07,322 --> 00:40:08,532
[scoffs] Really?

813
00:40:10,617 --> 00:40:12,035
Thanks.

814
00:40:12,077 --> 00:40:16,581
[guard]
Agent Cowan. Your ID.

815
00:40:16,623 --> 00:40:18,083
Oh, yeah. Thanks.

816
00:40:18,625 --> 00:40:19,668
[door buzzing]

817
00:40:22,129 --> 00:40:24,631
It appears Mr. Bradley's
still at dinner.

818
00:40:24,673 --> 00:40:27,425
Yeah? Tell him recess is over.

819
00:40:27,467 --> 00:40:28,927
[operatic music playing]

820
00:40:30,637 --> 00:40:31,721
[Dylan scoffs]

821
00:40:35,308 --> 00:40:36,351
What?

822
00:40:43,650 --> 00:40:45,026
[door buzzes and opens]

823
00:40:54,494 --> 00:40:55,871
All right, so I made my move.

824
00:40:55,912 --> 00:40:58,123
Where are they?
I don't have time for bullshit.

825
00:40:58,165 --> 00:41:00,709
Oh, I have all the time
in the world, thanks to you.

826
00:41:00,750 --> 00:41:04,212
And I didn't get to finish my lobster,
which makes me very grumpy.

827
00:41:04,254 --> 00:41:07,048
Okay, let's cut the crap.
What do you want?

828
00:41:07,090 --> 00:41:10,302
You can dispense with
the tough guy act to begin with.

829
00:41:10,343 --> 00:41:12,929
You're too desperate
for it to be believable.

830
00:41:15,015 --> 00:41:17,642
I said, what do you want?

831
00:41:17,684 --> 00:41:21,313
You used a form 219 warrant
to search my room.

832
00:41:21,354 --> 00:41:24,065
You found a connection
between me and the Four Horsemen.

833
00:41:24,107 --> 00:41:29,279
Which means you can take me
out of here on a 24-hour leave.

834
00:41:29,321 --> 00:41:33,575
- You want me to break you out?
- I want you to take me out.

835
00:41:33,617 --> 00:41:36,203
All you need is an extradition order,

836
00:41:36,244 --> 00:41:38,997
which you'll find in
that tray by my printer.

837
00:41:39,831 --> 00:41:45,253
Dylan, I had nothing to do
with the Horsemen's disappearance.

838
00:41:45,295 --> 00:41:47,797
You were lured into a trap.

839
00:41:47,839 --> 00:41:50,926
And like Dorothy did
when she landed in Oz,

840
00:41:50,967 --> 00:41:57,224
you're beginning to realize
that the only way out is through.

841
00:41:57,265 --> 00:42:00,310
And I'm the only one
who can get you there.

842
00:42:01,186 --> 00:42:02,604
You got this place wired.

843
00:42:02,646 --> 00:42:06,816
You don't need me to get out of here.
This is all about payback.

844
00:42:06,858 --> 00:42:10,695
- I believe in an eye for an eye.
- So you're out to destroy me?

845
00:42:10,737 --> 00:42:11,947
Oh, absolutely.

846
00:42:11,988 --> 00:42:13,281
You think I'm still gonna
play your little game?

847
00:42:13,323 --> 00:42:15,033
I know you will.

848
00:42:15,075 --> 00:42:19,120
Because no matter how hard you try
to find a culprit behind all this,

849
00:42:19,162 --> 00:42:21,581
you're going to blame only yourself.

850
00:42:21,623 --> 00:42:26,127
When your little vendetta ended with you
putting me in jail 18 months ago,

851
00:42:26,169 --> 00:42:30,090
you got tired, you got sloppy.
You stopped paying attention.

852
00:42:30,131 --> 00:42:32,217
And that's where you lost.

853
00:42:32,259 --> 00:42:33,760
[door buzzes and opens]

854
00:42:35,345 --> 00:42:38,890
So, you can save yourself,

855
00:42:40,600 --> 00:42:45,105
or you can make a deal with me,
and save the Four Horsemen,

856
00:42:45,146 --> 00:42:48,483
and stop wasting both of our time.

857
00:42:50,610 --> 00:42:56,074
Steal something for this narcissistic
little man boy? I don't like it.

858
00:42:56,116 --> 00:42:58,285
But what I like less
is you deciding for us.

859
00:42:58,326 --> 00:43:00,912
Yeah? Do you like that we're the
laughing stocks of the magic world,

860
00:43:00,954 --> 00:43:02,831
and the fugitives
of the actual world?

861
00:43:02,872 --> 00:43:04,624
Walter is right.
We have nowhere to go.

862
00:43:04,666 --> 00:43:05,959
But we can fix that.

863
00:43:06,001 --> 00:43:07,252
- We can fix it?
- Yeah.

864
00:43:07,294 --> 00:43:08,837
So you're officially
part of the team now?

865
00:43:08,878 --> 00:43:10,714
- Excuse me?
- I'm sure this is what Dylan

866
00:43:10,755 --> 00:43:12,882
meant when he said we should
all work as a single organism.

867
00:43:12,924 --> 00:43:16,219
Yeah, that is a fairytale
that Dylan tells himself, and tells us.

868
00:43:16,261 --> 00:43:18,930
Look, even if we get this stick,
he'll never let us go.

869
00:43:18,972 --> 00:43:23,101
We can't trust Walter, okay?
The Eye has a history in Macau.

870
00:43:23,143 --> 00:43:24,519
They're the only ones we can trust.

871
00:43:24,561 --> 00:43:25,603
Now, if we can get it to them,

872
00:43:25,645 --> 00:43:27,981
they can clear our names
and get us the hell out of here.

873
00:43:28,023 --> 00:43:29,566
[Lula] It's a bad plan, man.

874
00:43:31,359 --> 00:43:32,819
[door bells jingling]

875
00:43:37,198 --> 00:43:39,159
- Hey.
- [dinging]

876
00:43:39,200 --> 00:43:40,535
Hi, how are you?

877
00:43:40,577 --> 00:43:42,579
Um, we need some
things custom-made.

878
00:43:42,621 --> 00:43:44,247
Actually, by tomorrow.
We're kind of in a rush.

879
00:43:44,289 --> 00:43:45,999
And...

880
00:43:46,041 --> 00:43:48,293
You have no idea what
I'm talking about, do you?

881
00:43:48,960 --> 00:43:50,837
[both speaking Mandarin]

882
00:43:54,215 --> 00:43:57,510
Welcome to long's.
My name's Li. Not Bruce Lee.

883
00:43:57,552 --> 00:43:58,845
- What?
- Got you.

884
00:43:58,887 --> 00:43:59,971
- Okay.
- Look.

885
00:44:01,973 --> 00:44:03,016
Where'd it go?

886
00:44:05,602 --> 00:44:07,437
Oh! And now it's by my head. How fun.

887
00:44:07,479 --> 00:44:09,064
- $20.
- $20?

888
00:44:09,105 --> 00:44:11,024
No, thank you.
We're kind of in a rush.

889
00:44:11,066 --> 00:44:13,360
- $10.
- Uh, no.

890
00:44:13,401 --> 00:44:14,736
- Two for one.
- No.

891
00:44:14,778 --> 00:44:16,363
Okay, all right.
Just give us the thumbs. Yeah?

892
00:44:16,404 --> 00:44:18,698
Okay. Thanks a lot, Jack.
Please take these.

893
00:44:18,740 --> 00:44:21,409
So, we need a Keplinger holdout,

894
00:44:21,451 --> 00:44:25,497
and we also need roughing fluid,
a Sanada gimmick, sleeves, tracks.

895
00:44:25,538 --> 00:44:27,499
This is all in plastic,
though, if you can.

896
00:44:27,540 --> 00:44:28,958
[both speaking Mandarin]

897
00:44:32,045 --> 00:44:33,088
What?

898
00:44:35,298 --> 00:44:36,841
Is there a problem?

899
00:44:36,883 --> 00:44:40,095
My grandmother wants to know
why plastic? Plastic is cheap.

900
00:44:40,136 --> 00:44:42,430
Sorry. Yeah, we need plastic
because we're...

901
00:44:42,472 --> 00:44:46,101
We're going through a very sensitive
metal detector, okay?

902
00:44:46,142 --> 00:44:48,895
So plastic, nothing. Metal...

903
00:44:48,937 --> 00:44:50,939
[imitates alarm blaring]

904
00:44:50,980 --> 00:44:53,024
- It detects.
- [speaking Mandarin]

905
00:44:53,775 --> 00:44:56,152
[imitates alarm blaring]

906
00:44:57,529 --> 00:44:58,613
What did she say?

907
00:44:58,655 --> 00:45:02,033
She said just because you're
talking slowly and moving your hands

908
00:45:02,075 --> 00:45:04,119
doesn't mean she can suddenly
understand English.

909
00:45:04,160 --> 00:45:06,955
[clicks tongue]
Oh, yeah. So sorry. He's racist.

910
00:45:06,996 --> 00:45:11,251
Hey, bro. Listen, I know
that the only thing that we agree on

911
00:45:11,292 --> 00:45:13,920
is that our mom and dad
had one too many children.

912
00:45:13,962 --> 00:45:18,299
So why don't we just let
the kids play with their toys

913
00:45:18,341 --> 00:45:19,843
and go get a little drinkey-poo?

914
00:45:19,884 --> 00:45:25,265
- If it's free, it's me.
- Great. Guys, we'll be right back.

915
00:45:25,306 --> 00:45:28,977
[Chase] Okay, kiddies,
the chaperones are watching you.

916
00:45:29,018 --> 00:45:31,312
Don't do anything I wouldn't enjoy.

917
00:45:32,355 --> 00:45:34,441
[Atlas]
Okay. Have fun, you two.

918
00:45:36,776 --> 00:45:40,238
Hey. Can I use your phone?
It's kind of important.

919
00:45:40,280 --> 00:45:41,698
Sure.

920
00:45:42,490 --> 00:45:44,159
- On the house.
- Thanks.

921
00:45:45,785 --> 00:45:46,911
Who are you calling?

922
00:45:46,953 --> 00:45:48,455
[Atlas] I'm arranging
to hand over the stick.

923
00:45:48,496 --> 00:45:50,290
So that's how we've been
contacting the Eye?

924
00:45:50,331 --> 00:45:51,624
You've been doing it
on your own?

925
00:45:51,666 --> 00:45:52,834
Maybe.

926
00:45:52,876 --> 00:45:55,336
Oh, God.
Dylan's not gonna like this.

927
00:45:55,378 --> 00:45:57,464
I'm not really concerned
with what Dylan likes. Okay?

928
00:45:57,505 --> 00:45:58,798
I'm doing this for us.

929
00:46:00,925 --> 00:46:04,721
- What is wrong with this thing?
- Hey, relax, it's just a kid's toy.

930
00:46:04,762 --> 00:46:06,139
Yeah, that's what I thought.

931
00:46:06,181 --> 00:46:07,557
- Okay. Let me just...
- Ow!

932
00:46:07,599 --> 00:46:10,018
Sorry, sorry. Jesus.

933
00:46:12,020 --> 00:46:14,481
Hey, can you get this?

934
00:46:14,522 --> 00:46:15,690
[door buzzes]

935
00:46:19,027 --> 00:46:21,029
It's like birth, you know.

936
00:46:21,070 --> 00:46:24,574
One person enters the hospital,
two people come out.

937
00:46:24,616 --> 00:46:26,075
Walk and talk.

938
00:46:26,117 --> 00:46:28,495
I'll tell you on the plane.

939
00:46:28,536 --> 00:46:30,663
What plane?

940
00:46:30,705 --> 00:46:33,708
My sources tell me
your Horsemen are in Macau.

941
00:46:34,459 --> 00:46:36,753
- What's the look?
- It's none of your business.

942
00:46:36,795 --> 00:46:38,046
Who are your sources?

943
00:46:40,673 --> 00:46:42,800
Just some old friends.

944
00:46:45,053 --> 00:46:47,096
[both speaking Mandarin]

945
00:46:49,599 --> 00:46:52,644
When we have the card, where do I go?

946
00:46:52,685 --> 00:46:55,104
And 0 for 52.
[chuckles]

947
00:46:55,146 --> 00:46:58,233
Well, it's perfect.
It's a perfect score.

948
00:46:59,275 --> 00:47:02,153
Then what about girls?

949
00:47:02,195 --> 00:47:04,072
- Like, relationships?
- [groans]

950
00:47:04,113 --> 00:47:05,281
What?

951
00:47:09,118 --> 00:47:12,705
Look, it's not
something I'm proud of,

952
00:47:12,747 --> 00:47:18,836
but every girl I get close to,
I end up taking their trust.

953
00:47:18,878 --> 00:47:21,422
And then their wallet.

954
00:47:21,965 --> 00:47:23,132
So...

955
00:47:25,552 --> 00:47:28,137
- You take their wallets?
- Yeah.

956
00:47:30,306 --> 00:47:32,475
You ever take their belts?

957
00:47:33,893 --> 00:47:38,356
Or how about some peanuts
from the hotel bar?

958
00:47:38,398 --> 00:47:41,401
Not sure why you took those.

959
00:47:41,442 --> 00:47:44,571
I'm sorry, did you think
that I was like those other girls?

960
00:47:46,072 --> 00:47:47,907
Oh, Jack.

961
00:47:53,621 --> 00:47:55,832
[Atlas] Okay. So there's a marketplace
down the street.

962
00:47:55,873 --> 00:47:57,959
And I'm meeting
a man with a blue hat.

963
00:47:58,084 --> 00:48:00,837
He'll get the stick to the right people
and get us home.

964
00:48:00,878 --> 00:48:02,964
You go grab Merritt, okay?
We got a lot to do.

965
00:48:03,006 --> 00:48:04,757
And, hey, put your belt on.

966
00:48:04,799 --> 00:48:07,510
[stammers] Oh, no, it's not...
She took it off me and...

967
00:48:08,720 --> 00:48:11,598
[Merritt] You know, the most
heartbreaking moment of my life

968
00:48:11,639 --> 00:48:16,394
was when I discovered that you had
stolen all my money and split.

969
00:48:16,436 --> 00:48:18,563
I didn't realize until now

970
00:48:18,605 --> 00:48:21,107
how much of that money
you put into your face.

971
00:48:21,149 --> 00:48:25,778
Seriously, is it weird to have more hair
in your nose than on your head?

972
00:48:25,820 --> 00:48:28,406
Speaking of, next time
you get a hair transplant,

973
00:48:28,448 --> 00:48:34,120
you might wanna consider requesting
something other than old man pubes.

974
00:48:34,162 --> 00:48:38,249
You know what?
You are such a buffoon, Mer-Bear.

975
00:48:38,291 --> 00:48:40,251
And this little ploy you have

976
00:48:40,293 --> 00:48:44,422
of stalling me while your friends
screw over my employer?

977
00:48:44,464 --> 00:48:46,132
Not gonna work.

978
00:48:46,174 --> 00:48:47,342
[giggles]

979
00:48:48,468 --> 00:48:52,722
Chase! As you stare into my eyes,
you will find that you wanna sleep.

980
00:48:52,764 --> 00:48:55,433
When you wake, you will beg
for Merritt's forgiveness

981
00:48:55,475 --> 00:48:58,686
and realize that you will never be
half the man that he is.

982
00:48:58,728 --> 00:48:59,812
[slaps]

983
00:49:00,688 --> 00:49:07,403
Merritt, I am so,
so very, very sorry

984
00:49:07,445 --> 00:49:10,198
about how pathetic your pupil is.

985
00:49:10,239 --> 00:49:13,451
Hey, a little hint
on your technique of surprise.

986
00:49:13,493 --> 00:49:17,830
It lacks that all-essential
little element of surprise.

987
00:49:18,331 --> 00:49:22,710
Hey, this has been fun, Mer-Bear.
Let's do it again sometime.

988
00:49:26,130 --> 00:49:31,094
[Thaddeus] Well, I've had ample time
to do some research, and you know,

989
00:49:31,135 --> 00:49:32,220
I was wrong.

990
00:49:32,261 --> 00:49:35,890
I think the Eye
might actually be real.

991
00:49:35,932 --> 00:49:37,433
Thought you didn't
buy into all that.

992
00:49:37,475 --> 00:49:39,519
I'd be lying if I
said I didn't think

993
00:49:39,560 --> 00:49:42,939
that this road would lead to
the great wizard behind the curtain

994
00:49:42,980 --> 00:49:45,566
and, in the end,
I might get to see his face.

995
00:49:45,608 --> 00:49:46,859
That ain't gonna happen.

996
00:49:46,901 --> 00:49:48,486
Even if the fate of
the Horsemen depends on it?

997
00:49:48,528 --> 00:49:51,239
Listen to me. I broke you out of there.
We're not changing the terms now.

998
00:49:51,280 --> 00:49:54,033
- You put me there!
- Yeah, because you deserve to be there.

999
00:49:54,075 --> 00:49:57,662
- Listen, I did not kill your father.
- What?

1000
00:49:57,704 --> 00:50:00,665
All right, all right,
let's just cut the bullshit.

1001
00:50:00,707 --> 00:50:04,335
I know who you are, Shrike.

1002
00:50:05,628 --> 00:50:07,672
I know you blame me
for your father's death.

1003
00:50:07,714 --> 00:50:11,718
I know you think I goaded him into
performing a trick he couldn't pull off.

1004
00:50:11,759 --> 00:50:16,639
I know the time in jail was a result
of a 30-year revenge plot against me.

1005
00:50:16,681 --> 00:50:18,933
Supposing that's all true,
you think I'd tell you now?

1006
00:50:18,975 --> 00:50:20,184
Man...

1007
00:50:21,894 --> 00:50:23,563
Thirty years.

1008
00:50:23,604 --> 00:50:29,235
Thirty years, and the greatest long game
magic trick ever created.

1009
00:50:29,277 --> 00:50:33,114
Just to put me behind bars. Okay.

1010
00:50:34,657 --> 00:50:36,576
So how did it feel, seeing me there?

1011
00:50:37,577 --> 00:50:39,370
Was it all you hoped?

1012
00:50:39,412 --> 00:50:40,872
I don't know what you're talking about.

1013
00:50:40,913 --> 00:50:45,043
You're lying.
It was an empty experience.

1014
00:50:45,084 --> 00:50:47,170
And you wanna know how I know?

1015
00:50:48,212 --> 00:50:50,965
I know because you know.

1016
00:50:52,258 --> 00:50:56,888
There's always, always more
than what's on the surface.

1017
00:50:56,929 --> 00:50:59,348
So what, the past didn't happen,
and you're not who I think you are?

1018
00:50:59,390 --> 00:51:00,558
Now, don't tell me in 30 years

1019
00:51:00,600 --> 00:51:03,478
that's the first time you've
asked yourself that question.

1020
00:51:04,103 --> 00:51:07,482
I am not my father.
You're not getting in my head, okay?

1021
00:51:07,523 --> 00:51:10,068
You think you're luring me into a trap?
You're not.

1022
00:51:10,109 --> 00:51:12,779
Now, I am desperate,
which means I'm dangerous.

1023
00:51:12,820 --> 00:51:16,324
My only concern is the health
and well-being of the Horsemen.

1024
00:51:16,365 --> 00:51:19,869
And you're gonna lead me to them.
And if you don't, I promise you,

1025
00:51:19,911 --> 00:51:23,831
you're gonna end up far worse
than in some cushy jail cell somewhere.

1026
00:51:37,220 --> 00:51:40,848
[Thaddeus] What if the Horsemen
don't actually need you to save them?

1027
00:51:45,353 --> 00:51:48,189
[Atlas] All right. So the lab
is made up of two distinct layers,

1028
00:51:48,231 --> 00:51:51,317
the security perimeter
and the clean room.

1029
00:51:51,359 --> 00:51:53,402
The stick we're looking for
should be in this core.

1030
00:51:53,444 --> 00:51:55,530
So we're gonna have to
get underneath, extract it,

1031
00:51:55,571 --> 00:51:57,323
and replace it with a decoy.

1032
00:51:57,365 --> 00:51:58,741
Now, we're about to get to the chip.

1033
00:51:58,783 --> 00:52:00,409
This is the thing
about the chip, it's very thin.

1034
00:52:00,451 --> 00:52:03,371
Luckily, it's similar
in weight and size to a playing card,

1035
00:52:03,412 --> 00:52:05,331
so we're gonna have to
brush up on our card-istry.

1036
00:52:07,375 --> 00:52:08,459
Whoa, whoa!

1037
00:52:12,839 --> 00:52:14,048
That's no good.

1038
00:52:23,516 --> 00:52:25,768
[Atlas] So how do we get in?
Hannes Pike.

1039
00:52:25,810 --> 00:52:27,645
He's the son of
a South African gangster.

1040
00:52:27,687 --> 00:52:29,397
<i>He's RSVP'd with what looks like</i>

1041
00:52:29,438 --> 00:52:31,440
<i>a couple of members
of his security detail.</i>

1042
00:52:31,482 --> 00:52:34,527
<i>A doctor, to vet it, I guess,
and somebody named Buffy.</i>

1043
00:52:34,569 --> 00:52:38,281
[Lula] <i>Yeah, apparently, he travels
with a different bimbo every week. Hmm.</i>

1044
00:52:38,322 --> 00:52:40,992
I wonder which one of us
gets to play the bimbo.

1045
00:52:49,542 --> 00:52:51,460
Hey, can I get in?

1046
00:52:53,129 --> 00:52:54,714
At the soothing sound of the slots

1047
00:52:54,755 --> 00:52:58,176
you slip into a serene state
of slumber and sleep.

1048
00:52:59,635 --> 00:53:01,220
[Atlas] <i>Jack, for a moment,</i>

1049
00:53:01,262 --> 00:53:04,015
<i>they will think you're Hannes,
so lead them out and keep them busy.</i>

1050
00:53:04,056 --> 00:53:06,267
You trust your people implicitly.

1051
00:53:06,309 --> 00:53:08,394
You will have them
take care of everything,

1052
00:53:08,436 --> 00:53:09,896
and you will wait in the car.

1053
00:53:09,937 --> 00:53:13,524
- And eyes open, wide awake. Go.
- [snaps fingers]

1054
00:53:13,566 --> 00:53:15,401
[Jack] Excuse me.
These people are following me.

1055
00:53:15,443 --> 00:53:16,736
You might wanna
check their pockets.

1056
00:53:16,777 --> 00:53:18,237
[arguing in Cantonese]

1057
00:53:20,781 --> 00:53:23,117
[Atlas] <i>Then our time is
ticking to infiltrate the lab</i>

1058
00:53:23,159 --> 00:53:25,286
<i>and get the card to the market,
where I'll hand it off to the Eye,</i>

1059
00:53:25,328 --> 00:53:26,871
<i>so we can all get the hell home.</i>

1060
00:53:45,890 --> 00:53:49,185
Hannes, my old friend.
So glad you could make it.

1061
00:53:49,226 --> 00:53:52,355
I knew you had a soft spot
for an old-school bidding war.

1062
00:53:52,396 --> 00:53:53,522
How have you been?

1063
00:53:53,564 --> 00:53:57,235
I trust my people implicitly.
What they say goes.

1064
00:53:57,276 --> 00:54:00,404
Certainly. But I'm sure
you'd like to see it for yourself.

1065
00:54:00,446 --> 00:54:03,282
Hold it in your hands,
check the build quality.

1066
00:54:05,660 --> 00:54:08,287
Or not. Also fine.

1067
00:54:08,329 --> 00:54:10,373
Well, if you'd like to follow me.

1068
00:54:13,834 --> 00:54:18,297
You'll have to remove all your metal.
Watches, rings, etc.

1069
00:54:18,339 --> 00:54:20,716
- Yeah, of course.
- Excuse me for asking...

1070
00:54:20,758 --> 00:54:22,635
Where might I have seen you before?

1071
00:54:23,928 --> 00:54:26,389
I don't know, probably
one of my many symposiums.

1072
00:54:26,430 --> 00:54:27,556
The book jacket!

1073
00:54:27,598 --> 00:54:30,476
I have to say, Dr. Michaelakis,
I'm a huge fan.

1074
00:54:30,518 --> 00:54:32,395
[chuckling]
Oh, thank you so much.

1075
00:54:32,436 --> 00:54:34,981
Uh, which book?
There have been so many...

1076
00:54:36,065 --> 00:54:38,859
Does Hannes' chippy
always talk for you, Doctor?

1077
00:54:40,653 --> 00:54:41,696
Doctor?

1078
00:54:44,407 --> 00:54:48,160
Sorry, when you say "chippy,"
you are referring to Buffy here, yeah?

1079
00:54:48,202 --> 00:54:49,412
Of course.

1080
00:54:51,247 --> 00:54:55,710
Hannes prefers the term "floozy"
for all his boy toys.

1081
00:54:55,751 --> 00:54:58,838
- Yeah. He does. That's good.
- Noted.

1082
00:54:58,879 --> 00:55:00,965
By the way,
I got your email, Dr. Michaelakis.

1083
00:55:01,007 --> 00:55:02,550
You had a query about our ability

1084
00:55:02,591 --> 00:55:04,719
to maintain quantum coherence
at room temperature

1085
00:55:04,760 --> 00:55:09,348
without the use of dilution,
refrigerators, or error correction.

1086
00:55:09,390 --> 00:55:11,058
Do you care to elucidate?

1087
00:55:11,100 --> 00:55:12,476
- Right.
- Yeah.

1088
00:55:12,518 --> 00:55:14,520
Yes, I did send that email.

1089
00:55:14,562 --> 00:55:17,565
- The other day, I saw you.
- I did, I sent it. So what gives?

1090
00:55:17,606 --> 00:55:19,066
I'm sorry, what gives...

1091
00:55:19,108 --> 00:55:20,693
I think what she's trying to say...

1092
00:55:20,735 --> 00:55:22,737
Actually, the grown-ups
are having a meeting, Buffy.

1093
00:55:22,778 --> 00:55:24,071
Okay.

1094
00:55:24,113 --> 00:55:25,406
If you'll hold on to that.

1095
00:55:25,448 --> 00:55:27,199
- Yeah, sure, Doctor.
- Thank you.

1096
00:55:27,241 --> 00:55:29,744
Now, every seventh grader,
even the dumb ones,

1097
00:55:29,785 --> 00:55:31,871
know the second law
of thermodynamics.

1098
00:55:31,912 --> 00:55:35,666
"All ordered systems
tend toward disorder." Disorder!

1099
00:55:35,708 --> 00:55:40,379
So I'm going to ask you one
more time, sir, what gives?

1100
00:55:46,010 --> 00:55:49,221
Well, it's actually
topological quantum order.

1101
00:55:49,263 --> 00:55:52,350
The emergence of quantum effects
on a macroscopic level.

1102
00:55:52,391 --> 00:55:55,311
So that is, in fact, what gives.

1103
00:56:00,316 --> 00:56:01,442
Thank you.

1104
00:56:03,944 --> 00:56:05,488
[beeps]

1105
00:56:07,948 --> 00:56:12,036
You know,
Buffy is not a bad name for you.

1106
00:56:12,078 --> 00:56:15,706
You know, buff, firm, taut.

1107
00:56:15,748 --> 00:56:17,583
That's good.
Did you just find a thesaurus somewhere?

1108
00:56:17,625 --> 00:56:18,959
Nubile.

1109
00:56:19,001 --> 00:56:22,171
- That's good. Thank you. Okay.
- There we go.

1110
00:56:23,756 --> 00:56:24,882
[beeps]

1111
00:56:26,425 --> 00:56:28,552
- [alarm blaring]
- [gasps]

1112
00:56:32,348 --> 00:56:34,183
Sorry, sorry.

1113
00:56:41,190 --> 00:56:43,484
The stick's metal.
How are we going to get it out?

1114
00:56:43,526 --> 00:56:44,777
Yeah. I don't know.

1115
00:56:45,945 --> 00:56:47,780
[Allen] This is the housing.

1116
00:56:47,822 --> 00:56:52,409
820 million qubit miles
of digi-synaptic resonance.

1117
00:56:57,748 --> 00:57:00,209
But of course, what sets us apart
from anything else on the planet

1118
00:57:00,251 --> 00:57:05,005
is the processor, which we playfully
refer to as the Magic Broomstick.

1119
00:57:05,047 --> 00:57:06,090
The Broomstick?

1120
00:57:06,132 --> 00:57:09,885
Has the power to clear the contents
of any computing system on the planet

1121
00:57:09,927 --> 00:57:12,596
and then magically
sweep them into your bin.

1122
00:57:12,638 --> 00:57:15,307
Oh! Broomstick. That's funny.

1123
00:57:15,349 --> 00:57:18,144
Take a look, vet it however you'd like,

1124
00:57:18,185 --> 00:57:20,563
and tell Hannes we'll be
taking bids on Monday.

1125
00:57:20,604 --> 00:57:21,856
- Thank you.
- [Merritt gasps]

1126
00:57:21,897 --> 00:57:23,858
[sneezes]

1127
00:57:23,899 --> 00:57:26,610
Oh, my God.
I must be allergic to something in here.

1128
00:57:26,652 --> 00:57:28,612
What could you possibly be
allergic to in here?

1129
00:57:28,654 --> 00:57:31,866
- This room is hermetically sealed.
- [sneezes] That's it.

1130
00:57:31,907 --> 00:57:33,784
I'm allergic to hermetic seals.

1131
00:57:33,826 --> 00:57:35,578
If we could get him away
from the computer, please.

1132
00:57:35,619 --> 00:57:38,330
- That's the one thing.
- Just until he's recovered.

1133
00:57:38,372 --> 00:57:39,957
We're gonna need some anti-bac...

1134
00:57:41,083 --> 00:57:42,877
Do we have alcohol wipes?

1135
00:57:42,918 --> 00:57:45,296
Your hands need to be sterile
if you intend to get any closer.

1136
00:57:45,337 --> 00:57:47,548
- Do I make myself clear?
- [Merritt continues sneezing]

1137
00:57:49,216 --> 00:57:52,052
- [Atlas] Sorry. We couldn't...
- [Merritt] No, I'm fine.

1138
00:57:52,094 --> 00:57:53,345
...take his medicine into the country.

1139
00:57:53,387 --> 00:57:54,597
[Lula] Yeah...

1140
00:57:56,015 --> 00:57:57,933
[Merritt sneezes]

1141
00:57:57,975 --> 00:58:00,436
[Allen]
Can't risk any contamination.

1142
00:58:00,478 --> 00:58:03,272
You're gonna have to stay away
from the inner workings.

1143
00:58:03,314 --> 00:58:04,732
Thank you very much.
Thank you.

1144
00:58:04,773 --> 00:58:06,400
- All right. If you're done...
- Oh. Here you go.

1145
00:58:06,442 --> 00:58:08,194
Sorry about this.
Okay. I'm okay.

1146
00:58:08,235 --> 00:58:10,404
This happens to him sometimes.
It'll pass.

1147
00:58:10,446 --> 00:58:12,364
Allergies. Nothing you can do.

1148
00:58:12,406 --> 00:58:14,450
- Well, something you could do, Doctor.
- [Merritt sneezing]

1149
00:58:32,259 --> 00:58:33,802
[snorting]

1150
00:58:34,470 --> 00:58:35,513
[Atlas] Okay?

1151
00:58:42,520 --> 00:58:43,562
Search him, please.

1152
00:58:43,604 --> 00:58:45,064
[Lula]
Didn't we just do that?

1153
00:58:45,105 --> 00:58:46,482
Are you serious?

1154
00:58:46,524 --> 00:58:48,525
Okay. I wanna run
full diagnostics on the system.

1155
00:58:48,567 --> 00:58:50,361
[speaking Cantonese]

1156
00:58:50,402 --> 00:58:52,321
This is completely unnecessary.

1157
00:58:53,489 --> 00:58:55,366
[speaking Cantonese]

1158
00:59:21,850 --> 00:59:23,102
[guard] Up, up.

1159
00:59:23,143 --> 00:59:24,311
Okay.

1160
00:59:39,743 --> 00:59:40,828
[exhales]

1161
00:59:42,246 --> 00:59:44,415
Ah!

1162
00:59:44,456 --> 00:59:46,875
- [speaking Cantonese]
- Hey! I can walk on my own.

1163
00:59:54,425 --> 00:59:56,051
Whoa!

1164
00:59:56,093 --> 00:59:57,636
- [grunting]
- [speaking Cantonese]

1165
00:59:57,678 --> 00:59:58,721
Sorry.

1166
01:00:16,447 --> 01:00:17,573
Hey!

1167
01:00:17,614 --> 01:00:19,533
I can do that myself.

1168
01:00:19,575 --> 01:00:21,869
We just met, man.

1169
01:00:21,910 --> 01:00:23,329
Handsy, handsy, handsy.

1170
01:00:35,507 --> 01:00:36,550
Hey!

1171
01:00:36,592 --> 01:00:37,634
[whistles]

1172
01:00:37,676 --> 01:00:40,220
My eyes are up here, man.

1173
01:00:40,262 --> 01:00:41,722
- How do you like it?
- [gasps]

1174
01:00:47,519 --> 01:00:49,146
[coughs]

1175
01:01:01,241 --> 01:01:02,951
[speaking Cantonese]

1176
01:01:04,244 --> 01:01:05,371
[Atlas] Hey, I'm good.

1177
01:01:07,039 --> 01:01:08,082
Turn around.

1178
01:01:11,251 --> 01:01:12,836
[guards speaking Cantonese]

1179
01:01:23,138 --> 01:01:25,766
[squeaking]

1180
01:01:26,183 --> 01:01:27,476
Do you have anything?

1181
01:01:27,518 --> 01:01:29,228
I don't know.
Can't trust anybody.

1182
01:01:30,688 --> 01:01:32,981
- I'm good.
- They're clean.

1183
01:01:33,023 --> 01:01:34,358
[guard speaking Cantonese]

1184
01:01:34,400 --> 01:01:36,360
Do your final checks
and get them out of here.

1185
01:01:36,402 --> 01:01:38,779
Oh, we're walking
this way again. Yay.

1186
01:01:44,243 --> 01:01:47,871
[Lula]
I don't speak the language.

1187
01:01:54,253 --> 01:01:55,671
See?

1188
01:01:55,712 --> 01:01:57,548
What did I tell you, man?
We didn't have anything.

1189
01:01:58,590 --> 01:02:01,176
Thanks, pal. Appreciate that.

1190
01:02:02,803 --> 01:02:04,388
[speaking Cantonese]

1191
01:02:10,561 --> 01:02:11,645
[Atlas exclaims]

1192
01:02:17,067 --> 01:02:20,863
Something about a big white dance floor,
makes me wanna boogie.

1193
01:02:20,904 --> 01:02:23,198
Hey, thanks for having us.

1194
01:02:23,741 --> 01:02:25,701
That's great stuff.

1195
01:02:26,827 --> 01:02:28,328
[speaking Cantonese]

1196
01:02:28,370 --> 01:02:29,413
[beeps]

1197
01:02:31,748 --> 01:02:33,041
[chuckles] Okay.

1198
01:02:33,083 --> 01:02:35,586
You guys are pretty serious
about your security, huh?

1199
01:02:39,006 --> 01:02:40,632
- [speaking Cantonese]
- [Atlas] Okay.

1200
01:02:40,674 --> 01:02:44,178
Do I have all my things?
I feel like I came in with more stuff.

1201
01:02:44,219 --> 01:02:46,889
- Did I come in with more stuff?
- [speaking Cantonese]

1202
01:02:46,930 --> 01:02:49,141
- You don't think so?
- [beeps]

1203
01:02:51,268 --> 01:02:53,854
Uh, sir, I think you
still have my wallet.

1204
01:02:53,896 --> 01:02:56,565
Remember, I, uh, gave it
to you when I came in?

1205
01:02:56,607 --> 01:02:58,817
It would be nice to leave with it.

1206
01:03:03,614 --> 01:03:04,656
Wallet coming through.

1207
01:03:05,407 --> 01:03:06,658
[metallic clang]

1208
01:03:08,452 --> 01:03:09,953
[alarm blaring]

1209
01:03:12,498 --> 01:03:14,124
Sorry, my belt.

1210
01:03:19,797 --> 01:03:21,381
- [Lula] Uh...
- [beeps]

1211
01:03:21,423 --> 01:03:23,425
I guess that's everything, right?

1212
01:03:23,467 --> 01:03:24,593
Thank you.

1213
01:03:24,635 --> 01:03:27,221
- That is not a toy, Buffy.
- Sorry.

1214
01:03:32,392 --> 01:03:34,019
Go, go, go!

1215
01:03:37,981 --> 01:03:40,484
[tires screeching]

1216
01:03:40,526 --> 01:03:42,402
[Atlas] All right.
Drop me off at the market

1217
01:03:42,444 --> 01:03:44,238
so I can get this to the Eye.

1218
01:03:44,279 --> 01:03:45,531
You asked me to call you
when they started

1219
01:03:45,572 --> 01:03:47,699
running around like headless chickens.

1220
01:03:48,700 --> 01:03:50,118
Well, that's what's happening.

1221
01:03:50,911 --> 01:03:52,120
[scoffs]

1222
01:04:04,883 --> 01:04:07,553
This is where your sources
told you they'd be?

1223
01:04:07,594 --> 01:04:11,431
No, this is where my sources said
we might find an answer.

1224
01:04:12,516 --> 01:04:14,184
[bell dinging]

1225
01:04:15,894 --> 01:04:17,229
[speaking Mandarin]

1226
01:04:22,568 --> 01:04:24,361
She must be familiar with your work.

1227
01:04:24,403 --> 01:04:25,862
Excuse me.

1228
01:04:25,904 --> 01:04:29,116
Miss, have you seen these people?

1229
01:04:30,242 --> 01:04:33,412
[both speaking Mandarin]

1230
01:04:39,793 --> 01:04:42,212
She says her grandson
spoke to their leader.

1231
01:04:42,254 --> 01:04:43,463
He's in the back.

1232
01:04:44,089 --> 01:04:45,340
What?

1233
01:04:45,382 --> 01:04:47,301
No "Wow, you speak Mandarin"?

1234
01:04:47,342 --> 01:04:48,969
[speaking Mandarin]

1235
01:04:51,847 --> 01:04:53,307
[chuckling]

1236
01:04:53,348 --> 01:04:55,642
[speaking Mandarin]

1237
01:05:18,915 --> 01:05:21,126
Ah! The Coffin to the Beyond.

1238
01:05:21,168 --> 01:05:22,502
[chuckles]

1239
01:05:22,544 --> 01:05:27,132
It was always a flap,
or a trap or mirrors.

1240
01:05:28,342 --> 01:05:31,762
The audience thought
he'd just disappeared.

1241
01:05:32,763 --> 01:05:35,724
But he was always
hidden somewhere inside.

1242
01:05:47,361 --> 01:05:52,115
I believe that's the prototype
for the one your father had made.

1243
01:05:52,157 --> 01:05:55,535
He, like many others over the years,
ordered his supplies from here.

1244
01:05:56,286 --> 01:05:59,456
Ah! [snaps fingers]
Of course.

1245
01:05:59,498 --> 01:06:03,251
That's why you gave me the look
when I said they were in Macau.

1246
01:06:03,293 --> 01:06:05,504
Your father used to come here
when you were young.

1247
01:06:05,545 --> 01:06:07,339
Can I please get some space here?

1248
01:06:12,511 --> 01:06:16,598
If you think you're the only one who'd
wondered for 30 years what happened...

1249
01:06:17,015 --> 01:06:18,684
...you're not.

1250
01:06:18,725 --> 01:06:21,103
Lionel was a master magician.

1251
01:06:21,144 --> 01:06:22,688
Either he gamed the hinges,

1252
01:06:22,729 --> 01:06:26,274
so he could kick the door
and they would pop out,

1253
01:06:26,316 --> 01:06:30,195
or he had access to the lock
from the inside so he could pick it.

1254
01:06:30,237 --> 01:06:34,950
Word is the safe was made
from cheap metal, and it bowed.

1255
01:06:34,991 --> 01:06:40,664
Still, he always had
something up his sleeve.

1256
01:06:40,706 --> 01:06:47,379
Unless he'd reached the limit of
his capabilities and his clock ran out.

1257
01:06:47,421 --> 01:06:48,880
[breathes shakily]

1258
01:06:52,134 --> 01:06:56,680
Excuse me. My grandmother
has something you might want.

1259
01:07:00,392 --> 01:07:02,686
This was your father's.

1260
01:07:02,728 --> 01:07:04,980
He had several of these made.

1261
01:07:08,692 --> 01:07:10,110
[speaking Mandarin]

1262
01:07:24,332 --> 01:07:26,001
And the Horsemen?

1263
01:07:26,877 --> 01:07:29,045
I overheard them talking.

1264
01:07:29,087 --> 01:07:33,592
One of them, Atlas, he's meeting
someone at the market nearby.

1265
01:07:50,817 --> 01:07:52,444
[Cowan] As for former Agent Rhodes,

1266
01:07:52,486 --> 01:07:55,113
his location is now
your number one priority.

1267
01:07:55,155 --> 01:07:57,365
We're putting out an international APB.

1268
01:07:57,407 --> 01:08:00,202
We have Interpol, including cooperation
from local authorities.

1269
01:08:00,243 --> 01:08:01,536
Agent Cowan.

1270
01:08:01,578 --> 01:08:05,207
I'm assuming it was actually not you
who walked into Newburgh Federal Prison,

1271
01:08:05,248 --> 01:08:08,210
then walked out 30 minutes later
with Thaddeus Bradley?

1272
01:08:08,251 --> 01:08:10,212
- What?
- He used your ID.

1273
01:08:14,257 --> 01:08:16,259
What are you doing, Rhodes?

1274
01:08:17,302 --> 01:08:18,678
[indistinct chatter]

1275
01:08:43,662 --> 01:08:45,747
- Atlas, hey.
- Dylan.

1276
01:08:45,789 --> 01:08:47,374
- I blew it, I'm sorry.
- What are you doing here?

1277
01:08:47,415 --> 01:08:48,667
I'm here to help now.

1278
01:08:48,708 --> 01:08:50,043
Okay, we definitely
don't need your help.

1279
01:08:50,085 --> 01:08:51,419
I know I messed up, all right?

1280
01:08:51,461 --> 01:08:53,004
Yeah, you put everybody's
lives in danger.

1281
01:08:53,046 --> 01:08:55,423
- Where is everybody?
- Where is everybody?

1282
01:08:55,465 --> 01:08:57,175
I can't be seen with you,
actually, right now.

1283
01:08:57,217 --> 01:08:59,219
I got it now, okay?
I appreciate you taking

1284
01:08:59,261 --> 01:09:00,846
the time to take control
for a little while.

1285
01:09:00,887 --> 01:09:02,597
- Hey, I'm actually... Yeah?
- Yeah, but I got it now, all right?

1286
01:09:02,639 --> 01:09:03,723
- You do?
- Yeah.

1287
01:09:03,765 --> 01:09:05,141
You look like you can
get some rest, buddy.

1288
01:09:05,183 --> 01:09:07,727
- Who you meeting here?
- I'm not meeting anybody.

1289
01:09:07,769 --> 01:09:09,271
They told me at long's
you were meeting somebody.

1290
01:09:09,312 --> 01:09:11,273
At long's?
[chuckles]

1291
01:09:11,314 --> 01:09:14,150
Okay, yeah, no, I am, um...

1292
01:09:14,192 --> 01:09:16,653
I'm meeting somebody from the Eye.

1293
01:09:16,695 --> 01:09:17,946
Yeah, no, they agreed to meet me

1294
01:09:17,988 --> 01:09:21,032
to exchange this computer chip
for our lives back.

1295
01:09:21,074 --> 01:09:22,367
So that's what it's come to now.

1296
01:09:22,409 --> 01:09:24,244
I hope you're happy
with the situation you've put us in.

1297
01:09:24,286 --> 01:09:25,829
You're talking to the Eye?

1298
01:09:25,871 --> 01:09:26,997
Yeah.

1299
01:09:27,038 --> 01:09:28,915
Why are you talking to the Eye?

1300
01:09:29,875 --> 01:09:32,878
Atlas.
Atlas, give me the stick.

1301
01:09:32,919 --> 01:09:35,255
Dylan, you're not our
leader anymore, okay?

1302
01:09:35,297 --> 01:09:37,966
You're not our hero.
You're not FBI.

1303
01:09:38,008 --> 01:09:41,011
You're not a magician.
You're not really anything.

1304
01:09:41,052 --> 01:09:43,930
And we trusted you for a year.

1305
01:09:43,972 --> 01:09:46,391
So if you really wanna help us...
If you really... [clears throat]

1306
01:09:46,433 --> 01:09:49,102
If you really wanna help us,
you would leave.

1307
01:09:50,270 --> 01:09:51,646
[scoffs]

1308
01:09:57,485 --> 01:10:00,822
I get it. Cool. Bye.

1309
01:10:18,423 --> 01:10:19,674
Hello, hello!

1310
01:10:19,716 --> 01:10:22,552
Yeah, that was me you called
at the magic shop.

1311
01:10:23,011 --> 01:10:26,014
So much fun though, knowing you'd be
scurrying away from me at the lab

1312
01:10:26,056 --> 01:10:27,515
just to bring it to me here.

1313
01:10:27,557 --> 01:10:29,225
Did you actually think I'd let you go?

1314
01:10:29,267 --> 01:10:32,020
- How did you do that?
- Everyone has their button.

1315
01:10:32,062 --> 01:10:36,066
You push it and they go blind.
And yours, obviously, is ego.

1316
01:10:36,107 --> 01:10:37,651
"Stay the course.

1317
01:10:37,692 --> 01:10:40,487
<i>Great changes are in store.</i>

1318
01:10:40,528 --> 01:10:43,073
<i>Trust that your unique talents</i>

1319
01:10:43,114 --> 01:10:44,741
will not go unrecognized."

1320
01:10:45,951 --> 01:10:47,452
- That was you.
- Yeah.

1321
01:10:47,494 --> 01:10:49,037
Merritt downloaded all the files,

1322
01:10:49,079 --> 01:10:51,831
but how do you think
we were able to find him?

1323
01:10:51,873 --> 01:10:52,999
Your phone.

1324
01:10:54,876 --> 01:10:56,878
I asked to see the face
behind all of this.

1325
01:10:56,920 --> 01:11:00,131
What you actually put your phone on
was a bi-wave siphon pad.

1326
01:11:01,591 --> 01:11:05,845
Once again,
science beats magic.

1327
01:11:06,263 --> 01:11:08,598
- So, the stick?
- No.

1328
01:11:09,641 --> 01:11:10,892
[groaning]

1329
01:11:11,685 --> 01:11:12,727
I got it!

1330
01:11:12,769 --> 01:11:14,229
I got it. I got it.

1331
01:11:16,231 --> 01:11:18,149
- Fuck, Dylan!
- Wait, leave them!

1332
01:11:18,191 --> 01:11:19,693
You really think
I'm gonna walk away from you?

1333
01:11:19,734 --> 01:11:21,861
- Give me the stick!
- [groans]

1334
01:11:21,903 --> 01:11:23,029
Give me it!

1335
01:11:23,071 --> 01:11:26,074
All right.
Don't ever question me again. Beat it!

1336
01:11:27,742 --> 01:11:29,411
[pounding on door]

1337
01:11:36,876 --> 01:11:39,421
- So, the stick.
- Go to hell.

1338
01:11:40,213 --> 01:11:41,256
[scoffs] Boys.

1339
01:11:41,297 --> 01:11:42,882
[panicked shouting]

1340
01:11:47,220 --> 01:11:48,346
[grunting]

1341
01:11:53,685 --> 01:11:55,645
I'm sorry! I'm sorry!

1342
01:11:55,687 --> 01:11:56,813
[groans]

1343
01:12:11,911 --> 01:12:13,371
[Walter]
There's like 10 of you.

1344
01:12:13,413 --> 01:12:15,248
Come on, he's just doing tricks.

1345
01:12:15,290 --> 01:12:17,208
He's there! Go!

1346
01:12:44,736 --> 01:12:46,613
- [rabbit squeaks]
- [crowd laughing]

1347
01:12:47,322 --> 01:12:48,490
[yelps]

1348
01:13:05,840 --> 01:13:06,966
Oh...

1349
01:13:20,355 --> 01:13:21,773
[laughs]

1350
01:13:38,415 --> 01:13:40,667
[groaning]

1351
01:13:40,708 --> 01:13:45,547
Dylan, watch the pretty birdies fly.
And sleep.

1352
01:13:45,880 --> 01:13:49,217
- Doesn't work on me.
- Not even as a distraction?

1353
01:13:49,259 --> 01:13:50,426
- [metal clanks]
- [groans]

1354
01:13:51,886 --> 01:13:54,514
- Good job.
- Nice to be involved.

1355
01:13:54,556 --> 01:13:56,474
[Chase chuckles]

1356
01:14:02,772 --> 01:14:04,858
Hey, guys! Guys! Hey!

1357
01:14:04,899 --> 01:14:07,569
- I just saw Dylan, something happened.
- What do you mean you just saw Dylan?

1358
01:14:07,610 --> 01:14:09,696
Dylan's here?
What happened?

1359
01:14:09,737 --> 01:14:12,240
- Atlas.
- [stammers] I don't know.

1360
01:14:17,036 --> 01:14:18,246
[Jack] What are they doing?

1361
01:14:18,288 --> 01:14:20,748
[Atlas]
Those are Walter's men.

1362
01:14:20,790 --> 01:14:23,877
This is what they want.
[sighs]

1363
01:14:23,918 --> 01:14:26,171
What the hell?
How do you still have that?

1364
01:14:26,212 --> 01:14:27,881
[machine whirring]

1365
01:14:31,092 --> 01:14:32,927
Whoa. That's Lionel Shrike's safe.

1366
01:14:32,969 --> 01:14:35,513
What the hell
do they want with that?

1367
01:14:35,555 --> 01:14:37,348
Okay, we gotta
follow that truck.

1368
01:14:37,390 --> 01:14:40,768
[Atlas] They must have Dylan.
We don't have much time.

1369
01:14:43,146 --> 01:14:45,064
[Dylan breathing heavily]

1370
01:14:45,106 --> 01:14:46,399
[Dylan] What do you want?

1371
01:14:46,441 --> 01:14:51,112
You to understand something
very important.

1372
01:14:51,154 --> 01:14:54,449
We are mirror images.

1373
01:14:54,491 --> 01:14:55,825
You see, because like you,

1374
01:14:55,867 --> 01:14:58,161
I share a very deep connection
with my father.

1375
01:14:59,496 --> 01:15:04,501
And like you, I'll stop at nothing
to avenge any wrongs done to him.

1376
01:15:04,542 --> 01:15:06,586
- [punching]
- [Dylan groans]

1377
01:15:09,130 --> 01:15:12,717
You know the only difference
between your father and mine?

1378
01:15:12,759 --> 01:15:14,677
Mine's still alive.

1379
01:15:15,345 --> 01:15:16,596
Get him up.

1380
01:15:30,068 --> 01:15:34,447
So, this is the man

1381
01:15:34,489 --> 01:15:37,617
who spent a lifetime
plotting against me.

1382
01:15:39,577 --> 01:15:41,913
I wouldn't have known your face

1383
01:15:41,955 --> 01:15:45,500
if it had been on a billboard
outside my bedroom window.

1384
01:15:45,541 --> 01:15:49,254
But you have spent, what,
30 years thinking about mine?

1385
01:15:49,295 --> 01:15:50,588
When my father died,

1386
01:15:50,630 --> 01:15:52,799
your insurance company
denied my mother her claims.

1387
01:15:52,840 --> 01:15:54,217
- I wouldn't even have known...
- She died a pauper!

1388
01:15:54,259 --> 01:15:56,135
...who your mother was.

1389
01:15:56,177 --> 01:16:00,807
She was a digit, a nanobyte
in a stream of data.

1390
01:16:00,848 --> 01:16:02,850
Because nothing is personal to you

1391
01:16:02,892 --> 01:16:05,186
and everyone and everything
is just a number, isn't that so?

1392
01:16:05,228 --> 01:16:07,897
That is where you are wrong,
Mr. Rhodes.

1393
01:16:07,939 --> 01:16:12,902
Once you made yourself known
it became very personal.

1394
01:16:14,112 --> 01:16:15,989
- My son...
- Yeah, the sociopath.

1395
01:16:16,030 --> 01:16:20,660
Funny thing is, I have seven
so-called legitimate children.

1396
01:16:20,702 --> 01:16:23,746
Sniveling, snobbish, stupid runts.

1397
01:16:23,788 --> 01:16:27,792
I have one illegitimate child
who is a lot like me.

1398
01:16:27,834 --> 01:16:30,253
The point is,
he wants something,

1399
01:16:30,295 --> 01:16:35,466
and like any good parent, I will
stop at nothing to get it for him.

1400
01:16:35,508 --> 01:16:37,302
Your Horsemen have it.

1401
01:16:37,343 --> 01:16:41,681
You will turn it and them
over to us, now.

1402
01:16:41,723 --> 01:16:42,849
No.

1403
01:16:43,891 --> 01:16:46,519
[groaning]

1404
01:16:46,561 --> 01:16:49,355
[Walter] Dylan, I would like you
to really take this moment in

1405
01:16:49,397 --> 01:16:52,859
because this is the consequence
of your personal vendetta come to life

1406
01:16:52,900 --> 01:16:54,694
and staring you in the face.

1407
01:16:54,736 --> 01:16:56,529
I want you to know
that when you're gone,

1408
01:16:56,571 --> 01:16:57,655
we're not going to stop.

1409
01:16:57,697 --> 01:16:59,824
We're gonna destroy
everything you believe in,

1410
01:16:59,866 --> 01:17:02,118
starting with the Horsemen,
and ending with the Eye.

1411
01:17:02,160 --> 01:17:04,078
Now then, cast your mind back

1412
01:17:04,120 --> 01:17:07,290
to standing by the banks of the river
watching your father descend,

1413
01:17:07,332 --> 01:17:09,375
disgraced and discredited.

1414
01:17:09,417 --> 01:17:12,211
The horrid psychic pain
as you have relived for years.

1415
01:17:12,920 --> 01:17:16,257
I felt that same thing two years ago

1416
01:17:16,299 --> 01:17:19,427
as you drained not just my father's
fortune, but his dignity!

1417
01:17:19,969 --> 01:17:22,013
And yet you took pleasure from it.

1418
01:17:24,807 --> 01:17:27,435
This should bring back
some childhood memories.

1419
01:17:36,277 --> 01:17:37,403
[groans]

1420
01:17:52,960 --> 01:17:54,754
[pounding on door]

1421
01:17:54,796 --> 01:17:56,672
- Would you like some tea?
- Oh. Thank you.

1422
01:17:56,714 --> 01:17:57,840
[muffled grunting]

1423
01:18:12,355 --> 01:18:14,690
- You ready?
- Over to you.

1424
01:18:21,656 --> 01:18:22,740
Splash!

1425
01:18:23,157 --> 01:18:24,367
[chuckling]

1426
01:18:26,244 --> 01:18:27,662
Job done!

1427
01:18:43,261 --> 01:18:46,681
[Tressler] Hell is going to
seem like a day at the spa

1428
01:18:46,723 --> 01:18:49,225
by the time we're through
with these Horsemen.

1429
01:18:49,267 --> 01:18:51,978
- Wouldn't you say?
- You had me at "hell."

1430
01:18:52,019 --> 01:18:53,521
[muffled screaming]

1431
01:19:08,828 --> 01:19:11,247
- [gasping]
- [Lionel] <i>I love you so much.</i>

1432
01:19:11,289 --> 01:19:13,750
[yelling in frustration]

1433
01:19:13,791 --> 01:19:16,252
Always keep something up my sleeve.

1434
01:19:16,294 --> 01:19:18,004
[panting]

1435
01:20:14,435 --> 01:20:15,853
[clicking]

1436
01:20:32,537 --> 01:20:34,956
[sighs]

1437
01:20:34,997 --> 01:20:38,084
I wish I could dredge
from the muck of my soul

1438
01:20:38,125 --> 01:20:42,255
one speck of remorse,
but I can't.

1439
01:20:42,296 --> 01:20:48,761
So I'll stick to the business at hand
and try not to smile too broadly.

1440
01:20:48,803 --> 01:20:54,183
And, uh, thank you for delivering
Mr. Dylan Rhodes.

1441
01:20:54,934 --> 01:20:56,686
I take it it's done.

1442
01:20:57,979 --> 01:20:59,981
Literally hit the bottom.

1443
01:21:00,523 --> 01:21:06,320
- Now, where are the Horsemen?
- They're performers.

1444
01:21:06,362 --> 01:21:11,951
Their pride, their ego, their need
to be adored are all too powerful

1445
01:21:11,993 --> 01:21:13,911
to keep them out of
the limelight for long.

1446
01:21:13,953 --> 01:21:19,500
If they don't make themselves known,
you will find yourself

1447
01:21:19,542 --> 01:21:23,546
in a very similar position
to Mr. Rhodes.

1448
01:21:23,588 --> 01:21:27,466
- Are we clear about that?
- As clear as the water he's under.

1449
01:21:34,932 --> 01:21:38,519
You'll have the rest
when I have the Horsemen.

1450
01:22:10,760 --> 01:22:11,844
[all] Dylan!

1451
01:22:13,262 --> 01:22:15,640
[Jack]
Dylan, come on, buddy, breathe!

1452
01:22:15,681 --> 01:22:16,933
- Dylan.
- Dylan?

1453
01:22:16,974 --> 01:22:19,101
- [Merritt] Dylan, come on!
- [coughing]

1454
01:22:20,478 --> 01:22:22,188
[Dylan panting]

1455
01:22:23,314 --> 01:22:26,067
- You're okay.
- [sighing]

1456
01:22:26,108 --> 01:22:28,861
Jesus! You scared
the hell out of us, man.

1457
01:22:28,903 --> 01:22:32,573
- Are you all right, bro?
- Okay!

1458
01:22:32,615 --> 01:22:34,617
- Thank you!
- This is the least I could do.

1459
01:22:34,659 --> 01:22:36,619
No. There's a hell of a lot
less you could've done.

1460
01:22:36,661 --> 01:22:37,995
That was not an option.

1461
01:22:38,037 --> 01:22:39,956
You took a bullet for us, it was huge.

1462
01:22:39,997 --> 01:22:41,874
You really did, man.

1463
01:22:44,627 --> 01:22:46,379
Thanks for pulling me out.
Seriously.

1464
01:22:47,296 --> 01:22:48,673
[softly] Yeah.

1465
01:22:48,714 --> 01:22:50,883
[Lula] You got yourself out.
We did the easy part.

1466
01:22:50,925 --> 01:22:53,219
Literally, in my case,
I was just standing on the shore

1467
01:22:53,260 --> 01:22:54,595
while Atlas jumped down and got you.

1468
01:22:54,637 --> 01:22:56,222
- [chuckling]
- I'm serious.

1469
01:22:56,764 --> 01:22:58,683
Hey, you guys.
Something's not right.

1470
01:22:58,724 --> 01:23:00,476
- What's wrong?
- [Lula] What?

1471
01:23:02,061 --> 01:23:04,397
- It's fake.
- What?

1472
01:23:06,107 --> 01:23:07,692
[Lula] No, I had the stick.

1473
01:23:07,733 --> 01:23:10,403
The actual stick.
I swear, it was in my hand,

1474
01:23:10,444 --> 01:23:12,988
in the lab, and then I put it in
the little case thing.

1475
01:23:13,030 --> 01:23:15,199
- And I gave it to Atlas.
- Right, which I then gave to Dylan.

1476
01:23:15,241 --> 01:23:17,785
Is there any chance you've possibly
misplaced it at any point?

1477
01:23:17,827 --> 01:23:21,247
No, I took it from you
and then slipped it back in your coat

1478
01:23:21,288 --> 01:23:23,082
when I pushed you out.

1479
01:23:23,124 --> 01:23:26,377
Either way, we're left holding
a whole sack full of nada.

1480
01:23:26,419 --> 01:23:29,046
Yeah, but they're gonna come after us
as if we do have something.

1481
01:23:29,088 --> 01:23:32,466
No. Okay. I agree that somebody
got the better of us. Okay? Somehow.

1482
01:23:32,508 --> 01:23:34,969
But I don't agree
that we have a sack full of nada.

1483
01:23:35,010 --> 01:23:38,222
Because we're all here.
That's a sack full of something.

1484
01:23:39,181 --> 01:23:45,896
Listen, we all know that Walter is not
going to stop until he gets that chip.

1485
01:23:45,938 --> 01:23:49,525
And we're the only ones
that even know that he's alive.

1486
01:23:49,567 --> 01:23:54,196
We can't just walk away.
That's not what the Horsemen do.

1487
01:23:56,949 --> 01:23:58,784
There's a quote. Um...

1488
01:23:58,826 --> 01:24:00,286
It's actually by the magician

1489
01:24:00,327 --> 01:24:02,121
that made me wanna do this
in the first place.

1490
01:24:02,163 --> 01:24:04,123
It's, uh...

1491
01:24:04,165 --> 01:24:10,880
"A magician's greatest power lies
forever shrouded in his empty fist."

1492
01:24:10,921 --> 01:24:13,299
"And the very idea
that he can convince the world

1493
01:24:13,340 --> 01:24:16,510
that he is, in fact,
carrying with him a secret."

1494
01:24:16,552 --> 01:24:19,430
- That's Lionel Shrike.
- Right.

1495
01:24:20,639 --> 01:24:21,766
[Jack] So what are you saying?

1496
01:24:21,807 --> 01:24:25,060
That we should pretend like
we have something we don't?

1497
01:24:28,063 --> 01:24:31,525
- What is Walter's greatest fear?
- Being seen.

1498
01:24:31,567 --> 01:24:35,613
- And what does the stick do?
- The stick can unencode anything.

1499
01:24:35,654 --> 01:24:40,618
It can open up a back door
into any computer on the planet.

1500
01:24:40,659 --> 01:24:42,703
- Including his.
- Yeah.

1501
01:24:44,288 --> 01:24:46,749
Right, we not only make him
think that we have it,

1502
01:24:46,791 --> 01:24:50,920
but that we're going to use it
to expose and destroy him.

1503
01:24:50,961 --> 01:24:54,381
We need a plan.
But we don't have time.

1504
01:24:54,423 --> 01:24:57,927
We have each other
and there are five of us.

1505
01:24:57,968 --> 01:25:00,930
But we also need supplies, right?
And resources.

1506
01:25:00,971 --> 01:25:04,266
And probably more than five people.

1507
01:25:04,308 --> 01:25:08,229
Do you really think
you don't have help?

1508
01:25:08,270 --> 01:25:11,065
Oh, she speaks English.
Of course. Yeah.

1509
01:25:11,107 --> 01:25:16,570
Do you know why the Fool is
the most powerful card in the tarot?

1510
01:25:16,612 --> 01:25:20,282
Not because the person
who draws him is a fool.

1511
01:25:20,324 --> 01:25:24,787
He's a fool because he's a clean slate,

1512
01:25:24,829 --> 01:25:28,791
and, therefore, can become anything.

1513
01:25:28,833 --> 01:25:30,167
You were chosen.

1514
01:25:30,918 --> 01:25:32,753
All of you.

1515
01:25:32,795 --> 01:25:38,050
Not because of who you are,
but because of who you might become.

1516
01:25:39,635 --> 01:25:43,514
When you say "chosen"...
Are you part of the Eye?

1517
01:25:43,556 --> 01:25:47,643
Yes. We are part of the Eye.

1518
01:25:47,685 --> 01:25:50,938
You've each doubted our existence.

1519
01:25:51,730 --> 01:25:56,068
Wondering if we,
indeed, were watching.

1520
01:25:59,655 --> 01:26:03,325
We are.
We always have been.

1521
01:26:03,367 --> 01:26:05,911
This is the best
magic shop in the world.

1522
01:26:05,953 --> 01:26:08,205
- You know what she's saying, right?
- Yes.

1523
01:26:08,247 --> 01:26:10,666
That now we have
resources and help.

1524
01:26:12,459 --> 01:26:13,836
[softly] Thank you.

1525
01:26:16,297 --> 01:26:18,007
So, who's in?

1526
01:26:21,760 --> 01:26:24,388
- I'm in.
- Yeah, I'm in.

1527
01:26:27,183 --> 01:26:28,225
Let's do this.

1528
01:26:30,603 --> 01:26:32,229
[all speaking Mandarin]

1529
01:26:39,236 --> 01:26:40,446
[cell phone chimes]

1530
01:26:45,910 --> 01:26:47,661
[softly] No, no, no.

1531
01:26:50,247 --> 01:26:52,416
<i>Not long ago, we were tricked.</i>

1532
01:26:52,458 --> 01:26:55,419
<i>I was exposed
and brought back from the dead.</i>

1533
01:26:55,461 --> 01:26:58,339
[Lula] <i>So we thought it was only fitting
that we do the same thing</i>

1534
01:26:58,380 --> 01:27:02,760
<i>- to the person who did it to us.
- Midnight, New Year's Eve. London.</i>

1535
01:27:02,801 --> 01:27:06,096
<i>We will be performing a series of shows
that all connect to our big finale,</i>

1536
01:27:06,138 --> 01:27:08,307
<i>so pay close attention to each trick.</i>

1537
01:27:08,349 --> 01:27:09,475
Get my father.

1538
01:27:11,602 --> 01:27:12,728
Run!

1539
01:27:12,770 --> 01:27:15,981
I want Interpol, Scotland Yard,
whoever we have in London.

1540
01:27:16,023 --> 01:27:17,316
What do we know about Rhodes?

1541
01:27:17,358 --> 01:27:19,234
Wherever the Horsemen are,
that's where he is.

1542
01:27:19,276 --> 01:27:20,444
Let's get to the airport.

1543
01:27:20,486 --> 01:27:22,905
[Merritt] <i>So leave your kiddies
at home and get ready for a wild night,</i>

1544
01:27:22,947 --> 01:27:26,075
<i>because we, too, will bring
someone back from the dead.</i>

1545
01:27:26,116 --> 01:27:27,952
Let's move, everyone!

1546
01:27:27,993 --> 01:27:29,912
[Atlas] <i>In front of
the largest stage in the world...</i>

1547
01:27:29,954 --> 01:27:31,914
<i>The actual world.</i>

1548
01:27:31,956 --> 01:27:35,751
You know they're playing you, right?
Leading you into a trap?

1549
01:27:35,793 --> 01:27:37,503
Yeah, but the threat is real.

1550
01:27:37,544 --> 01:27:40,255
This card can hack into any system
on the planet, including ours.

1551
01:27:40,297 --> 01:27:42,549
They have it, why wouldn't
they use it to expose us?

1552
01:27:42,591 --> 01:27:44,134
Me. Everything we've done.

1553
01:27:44,176 --> 01:27:46,261
Is it real, Mr. McKinney?

1554
01:27:53,602 --> 01:27:54,895
The threat is real.

1555
01:27:54,937 --> 01:27:57,231
So, how do we stay
ahead of them?

1556
01:27:57,273 --> 01:27:59,692
[Chase] We need to get
to London by midnight.

1557
01:28:08,367 --> 01:28:09,910
[female reporter 1]
<i>We are here in London</i>

1558
01:28:09,952 --> 01:28:12,496
<i>on this New Year's Eve,
and the crowds are out in force.</i>

1559
01:28:12,538 --> 01:28:14,039
[male reporter 1]
<i>Locals and tourists alike</i>

1560
01:28:14,081 --> 01:28:16,250
<i>getting ready for
the party of the year.</i>

1561
01:28:16,291 --> 01:28:18,252
[female reporter 2]
<i>A video gone viral from the infamous</i>

1562
01:28:18,293 --> 01:28:20,170
<i>Horsemen magicians has surfaced.</i>

1563
01:28:20,212 --> 01:28:21,922
[male reporter 2] <i>They promise
to make a grand reappearance.</i>

1564
01:28:21,964 --> 01:28:25,092
[male reporter 1] <i>But will it end in
their arrest on national television?</i>

1565
01:28:25,134 --> 01:28:26,844
<i>Or some sort of vindication?</i>

1566
01:28:26,885 --> 01:28:29,013
<i>Who knows where they'll show up...</i>

1567
01:28:29,054 --> 01:28:30,472
[female reporter 1]
<i>But we do know, wherever,</i>

1568
01:28:30,514 --> 01:28:33,684
<i>whenever that is,
people will be watching.</i>

1569
01:28:35,352 --> 01:28:37,313
Yeah, texts, tweets, Instagrams.

1570
01:28:37,354 --> 01:28:40,357
Anything that says "Horsemen,"
brags about seeing the Horsemen,

1571
01:28:40,399 --> 01:28:42,109
tag them and bundle them.

1572
01:28:42,151 --> 01:28:44,570
Dad, who do we have security-wise
on this? Your guys?

1573
01:28:44,611 --> 01:28:45,821
Whoever you want.

1574
01:28:45,863 --> 01:28:47,781
Well, we want all of them
and all their friends.

1575
01:28:47,823 --> 01:28:49,908
Anyone who wants to work
stationed throughout the city,

1576
01:28:49,950 --> 01:28:51,785
so they can be anywhere in 60 seconds.

1577
01:28:51,827 --> 01:28:53,370
[tires screeching]

1578
01:28:54,538 --> 01:28:55,831
[man playing drums]

1579
01:29:06,050 --> 01:29:08,344
- Hello! Hey!
- [crowd cheers]

1580
01:29:10,262 --> 01:29:12,097
My name's Jack Wilder.

1581
01:29:12,890 --> 01:29:14,892
Goddamn, it feels good to be back.

1582
01:29:14,933 --> 01:29:18,562
- [cameras clicking]
- All right, gather around. Indulge me.

1583
01:29:18,604 --> 01:29:20,856
I wanna talk to you about
something real quick.

1584
01:29:20,898 --> 01:29:24,818
You all know Three Card Monte,
also known as "Find the Lady"?

1585
01:29:24,860 --> 01:29:29,198
Trick performed by street hustlers all
over the world. And why street hustlers?

1586
01:29:29,239 --> 01:29:32,159
Because as soon as you walk up
to the table, you lose.

1587
01:29:32,201 --> 01:29:34,203
Every time.
Let me demonstrate.

1588
01:29:35,037 --> 01:29:36,580
[all cheer]

1589
01:29:36,622 --> 01:29:40,793
While we're at it,
let's find ourselves a life-sized Queen.

1590
01:29:40,834 --> 01:29:42,795
Ma'am, would you
mind being my Queen?

1591
01:29:46,090 --> 01:29:48,467
Don't worry. I promise you
there's a 50 percent chance

1592
01:29:48,509 --> 01:29:49,843
you'll get her back after the show.

1593
01:29:49,885 --> 01:29:51,720
Head over there.
Thank you very much.

1594
01:29:51,762 --> 01:29:55,307
All right. Let's find ourselves
some Jacks to serve our Queen!

1595
01:29:55,349 --> 01:29:56,683
[Chase] <i>Trust me, gentlemen.</i>

1596
01:29:56,725 --> 01:30:00,521
I know how these guys work now.
They're gonna start with a tease.

1597
01:30:00,562 --> 01:30:02,564
A few little pop-ups.

1598
01:30:02,606 --> 01:30:05,526
<i>Something to lure you in. Like...</i>

1599
01:30:05,567 --> 01:30:09,738
Well, you know, like Three Card Monte,
where the guy goes,

1600
01:30:09,780 --> 01:30:12,366
"Looky here, but no, no, looky here!"

1601
01:30:12,407 --> 01:30:16,370
<i>Except when all these
little tricks are done,</i>

1602
01:30:16,412 --> 01:30:18,539
<i>the only thing
you're gonna be looking at</i>

1603
01:30:18,580 --> 01:30:22,584
is the inside of your own colon,
with the words

1604
01:30:22,626 --> 01:30:25,587
<i>"Horsemen" written all over it.</i>

1605
01:30:26,296 --> 01:30:27,881
In blood.

1606
01:30:27,923 --> 01:30:31,426
We get the picture, Mr. McKinney.

1607
01:30:31,468 --> 01:30:33,554
And get out of my chair.

1608
01:30:33,595 --> 01:30:35,848
[Lula] Hello, everybody!

1609
01:30:35,889 --> 01:30:37,891
- Come close, come on!
- [applause]

1610
01:30:37,933 --> 01:30:39,893
All right, all right, so listen.

1611
01:30:39,935 --> 01:30:45,440
Tonight, I am going to make
something fly using actual magic.

1612
01:30:45,482 --> 01:30:47,276
- Are you ready?
- [all] Yeah!

1613
01:30:47,317 --> 01:30:50,404
I'm going to take
a very large vessel,

1614
01:30:50,446 --> 01:30:54,825
I'm gonna make it fly over there
and land on the Thames.

1615
01:30:54,867 --> 01:30:56,743
Can you handle that?

1616
01:30:56,785 --> 01:30:58,370
[Jack]
Same rules apply as before.

1617
01:30:58,412 --> 01:31:00,539
All you need to do is
keep your eye on the Queen.

1618
01:31:00,581 --> 01:31:01,957
It's as simple as that.

1619
01:31:01,999 --> 01:31:03,750
- Are you guys ready?
- [all] Yeah!

1620
01:31:03,792 --> 01:31:05,294
[Walter] Dad, look at this.

1621
01:31:06,587 --> 01:31:07,963
Tag this one.
Where does it come from?

1622
01:31:08,005 --> 01:31:10,174
Near the river.
Looks like the shows are starting.

1623
01:31:10,215 --> 01:31:11,758
But we're not the only ones
who found them.

1624
01:31:11,800 --> 01:31:13,427
- What do you mean?
- It's on Channel One.

1625
01:31:21,685 --> 01:31:22,936
- [Austin] Let's go to 2.
- [Cowan] Here we go.

1626
01:31:22,978 --> 01:31:25,606
Got him. We have a location.

1627
01:31:25,647 --> 01:31:27,649
It's Jack Wilder.
Here come the Horsemen.

1628
01:31:27,691 --> 01:31:29,693
Okay, we're moving.
Let's go, let's go.

1629
01:31:29,735 --> 01:31:31,487
Typing in grid coordinates now.

1630
01:31:33,238 --> 01:31:35,908
Turn around.
Hide yourselves with the cards.

1631
01:31:36,533 --> 01:31:39,745
And here we go. Switch!

1632
01:31:41,205 --> 01:31:43,373
You guys still have your eye on her?
You want me to go back and do it?

1633
01:31:43,415 --> 01:31:46,543
Okay, all right. I'm moving on.
And switch.

1634
01:31:48,462 --> 01:31:49,546
Where is she?

1635
01:31:49,588 --> 01:31:50,839
[crowd shouting]

1636
01:31:50,881 --> 01:31:52,966
Down at the end?
You sure?

1637
01:31:53,008 --> 01:31:55,844
All right, can I get a drumroll
from my man in the back?

1638
01:31:55,886 --> 01:31:57,846
- [drumroll]
- Thank you very much.

1639
01:31:59,056 --> 01:32:00,599
- Uh-oh.
- [crowd gasps]

1640
01:32:01,308 --> 01:32:02,476
Uh-oh.

1641
01:32:03,727 --> 01:32:06,230
- There's my girl.
- [laughs]

1642
01:32:06,271 --> 01:32:08,941
[stammers]
Not my girl, 100 percent your girl.

1643
01:32:08,982 --> 01:32:10,359
But just in this situation.

1644
01:32:10,400 --> 01:32:13,070
Okay, but I gotta warm up
a little bit first. Okay?

1645
01:32:13,111 --> 01:32:17,032
So, uh, let me just
make something small fly, like...

1646
01:32:17,074 --> 01:32:19,243
Fly, fly, fly!

1647
01:32:19,284 --> 01:32:22,704
Wow, right? Look at that!
Aw. Come on, people.

1648
01:32:22,788 --> 01:32:25,707
Tough crowd. You, fly!

1649
01:32:25,749 --> 01:32:26,917
- Me?
- Check your fly.

1650
01:32:28,085 --> 01:32:29,711
[crowd gasps]

1651
01:32:29,753 --> 01:32:32,047
- [applause]
- You like that?

1652
01:32:32,089 --> 01:32:34,007
You support that relationship?

1653
01:32:34,049 --> 01:32:36,969
That guy had a bird in his pants.
That's disgusting.

1654
01:32:40,597 --> 01:32:42,683
[dispatcher] <i>Copy that.
We've got two sightings reported.</i>

1655
01:32:42,724 --> 01:32:45,686
<i>- Heading to Greenwich Market.</i>
- Get me Thaddeus.

1656
01:32:45,727 --> 01:32:48,063
<i>Thaddeus, the FBI are here.
They're moving.</i>

1657
01:32:48,105 --> 01:32:51,233
Let 'em move.
That's what the Horsemen want.

1658
01:32:51,275 --> 01:32:52,985
Well, what if they get there first?
That can't happen.

1659
01:32:53,026 --> 01:32:55,195
<i>I guarantee you, they won't.</i>

1660
01:32:55,237 --> 01:32:56,488
Find the pattern.

1661
01:32:57,406 --> 01:33:00,409
You do that, and you'll be able
to cut them off

1662
01:33:00,450 --> 01:33:02,869
<i>before they get to their final trick.</i>

1663
01:33:02,911 --> 01:33:06,665
If it makes you feel better,
I'll take care of the FBI.

1664
01:33:08,667 --> 01:33:10,711
[indistinct chatter]

1665
01:33:15,716 --> 01:33:17,134
[crowd cheering]

1666
01:33:19,928 --> 01:33:22,389
OK, well, I guess you found me!

1667
01:33:22,431 --> 01:33:24,057
We've got a third spot.

1668
01:33:24,099 --> 01:33:26,643
Okay, everybody,
we're getting a pattern.

1669
01:33:28,979 --> 01:33:34,067
Um... Give me two, 13 and 21.

1670
01:33:35,110 --> 01:33:38,030
What the hell is that?
Freeze that and zoom in.

1671
01:33:40,115 --> 01:33:42,909
How the hell did this happen?

1672
01:33:42,993 --> 01:33:46,163
He's dead. We watched him drown.
How the hell did this happen?

1673
01:33:46,204 --> 01:33:48,749
Given that it did happen,
the pertinent question is,

1674
01:33:48,790 --> 01:33:49,833
what are we gonna do about it?

1675
01:33:49,875 --> 01:33:51,668
We're gonna stop him, Dad.
We'll stop him.

1676
01:33:51,710 --> 01:33:52,836
Where's my coat?

1677
01:33:52,878 --> 01:33:55,630
Walter, for the record,
I never loved the safe idea.

1678
01:33:55,672 --> 01:33:57,257
[Walter] Oh, I know
where they're going.

1679
01:33:57,299 --> 01:33:59,926
The next show is Merritt's
and it's by the river.

1680
01:33:59,968 --> 01:34:01,386
Chase, you need
to get to him

1681
01:34:01,428 --> 01:34:03,472
so we can find the Horsemen's
entry point for the finale.

1682
01:34:03,513 --> 01:34:05,307
[tires screeching]

1683
01:34:09,269 --> 01:34:12,981
I have a confession to make. I've been
told I have some control issues.

1684
01:34:13,023 --> 01:34:16,401
I've learned that it's really,
really hard to control people,

1685
01:34:16,443 --> 01:34:20,405
so I'm gonna try to control something
that's a lot easier than people.

1686
01:34:20,447 --> 01:34:21,865
I'm gonna try to
control the weather.

1687
01:34:21,907 --> 01:34:24,743
- [laughing]
- Yeah, rain, um...

1688
01:34:26,203 --> 01:34:27,871
It'd be a little difficult
to make it rain, right?

1689
01:34:27,913 --> 01:34:30,707
That would be something
that only God can do, right?

1690
01:34:30,749 --> 01:34:33,085
I'm gonna do something
that God can't do.

1691
01:34:33,126 --> 01:34:36,046
I'm not just gonna make it clear up.
No, no, no.

1692
01:34:36,088 --> 01:34:38,215
I'm gonna make it actually stop.

1693
01:34:39,591 --> 01:34:41,343
[crowd cheering]

1694
01:34:44,221 --> 01:34:45,722
[crowd gasps]

1695
01:34:51,478 --> 01:34:54,731
And can God do that?
Mmm. No, I don't think so.

1696
01:34:54,773 --> 01:34:57,150
Or what about make it go up?

1697
01:34:57,859 --> 01:34:59,569
[crowd gasps]

1698
01:35:04,783 --> 01:35:06,827
Are you still with me?

1699
01:35:06,868 --> 01:35:09,955
Watch the Queen on the left.
Let's do it. Turn around.

1700
01:35:13,291 --> 01:35:14,459
Switch!

1701
01:35:18,130 --> 01:35:19,339
Show me the lady.

1702
01:35:19,381 --> 01:35:22,217
Show me the lady!

1703
01:35:22,259 --> 01:35:23,468
The end? End?

1704
01:35:25,929 --> 01:35:27,973
You know what?
I'm actually starting to feel kinda bad.

1705
01:35:29,057 --> 01:35:32,185
It's just because I can actually feel
that you guys are paying attention.

1706
01:35:32,227 --> 01:35:33,895
It's just that...

1707
01:35:33,937 --> 01:35:37,399
You know, it's unfortunate
that it's the wrong kind of attention.

1708
01:35:38,608 --> 01:35:41,111
Yeah, we need a fresher bird.

1709
01:35:42,279 --> 01:35:45,407
He's so cute. He's so cute!

1710
01:35:45,449 --> 01:35:48,243
- Let's kill him, right?
- [crowd gasps]

1711
01:35:48,285 --> 01:35:52,289
- Merritt, move into position.
- Got it, Dylan.

1712
01:35:52,330 --> 01:35:54,040
Uh, I'm on my way.
I'll see you there.

1713
01:35:54,082 --> 01:35:56,501
Lula, stand by, all right?

1714
01:35:56,543 --> 01:35:58,920
Or, what about just go,
I don't know, just go insane?

1715
01:35:59,588 --> 01:36:01,381
[crowd exclaims]

1716
01:36:08,430 --> 01:36:10,932
[female reporter] <i>Reports are
coming in from all over London</i>

1717
01:36:10,974 --> 01:36:14,603
<i>as the Horsemen appear to have taken
over the whole city for their show.</i>

1718
01:36:17,606 --> 01:36:21,318
Hey, broski-whaddya-knowski?
Where you headed?

1719
01:36:21,359 --> 01:36:22,694
- Please, bro, don't do this.
- Where are you headed?

1720
01:36:22,736 --> 01:36:24,571
North, south, east?

1721
01:36:25,405 --> 01:36:26,948
East. Tower of London?

1722
01:36:26,990 --> 01:36:29,784
Tower Bridge?
Near Tower Bridge? The Thames!

1723
01:36:29,826 --> 01:36:34,414
[chuckles] You're going to
the Thamesy-Whemsy! You're so easy!

1724
01:36:34,456 --> 01:36:37,125
Bro, if there's any chance of us
ever having a relationship...

1725
01:36:37,167 --> 01:36:39,586
There's not.
Where's your entry?

1726
01:36:39,628 --> 01:36:43,465
South Bank? Greenwich? Greenwich.

1727
01:36:43,507 --> 01:36:47,177
[mocking] I know where you're going.
I know where...

1728
01:36:48,470 --> 01:36:49,888
Watch it, hobo.

1729
01:36:50,722 --> 01:36:52,724
[cell phone ringing]

1730
01:36:52,766 --> 01:36:55,310
Hey, Merritt. Oh, come on.
Tell me you're kidding. How?

1731
01:36:57,062 --> 01:36:58,480
When?

1732
01:36:58,522 --> 01:37:01,191
Shit. All right. All right, I got it.

1733
01:37:01,233 --> 01:37:03,318
Don't worry about it.
I'll warn the others.

1734
01:37:03,360 --> 01:37:04,819
[crowd clamoring]

1735
01:37:06,238 --> 01:37:07,948
Sorry. Just...

1736
01:37:07,989 --> 01:37:10,534
- [grunts]
- [crowd gasps]

1737
01:37:10,575 --> 01:37:11,701
- What? I just told you...
- [cell phone buzzing]

1738
01:37:11,743 --> 01:37:12,786
Phone call.

1739
01:37:14,162 --> 01:37:15,288
- Hello?
- [Dylan] <i>Lula.</i>

1740
01:37:15,330 --> 01:37:18,708
Dylan. Ah, yeah, kind of in the middle
of something right now.

1741
01:37:18,750 --> 01:37:21,378
<i>Wrap it up.
Meet me at the rendezvous point now.</i>

1742
01:37:21,419 --> 01:37:22,712
- What?
<i>- Now!</i>

1743
01:37:23,380 --> 01:37:25,382
Was that an act of God?

1744
01:37:25,423 --> 01:37:28,552
No. No, no, no,
that was an act of me

1745
01:37:28,593 --> 01:37:31,805
and the strobe lights
and rain machines.

1746
01:37:31,846 --> 01:37:33,807
And I hope you guys
were paying attention.

1747
01:37:33,849 --> 01:37:36,059
Because you're gonna need to know
all of that for the final.

1748
01:37:36,101 --> 01:37:37,477
[all cheering]

1749
01:37:39,604 --> 01:37:42,732
So how did I do it?
Did I use a Barry Trap?

1750
01:37:42,774 --> 01:37:45,110
Maybe some switches
or a few duplicates?

1751
01:37:45,151 --> 01:37:46,236
[Dylan] <i>Jack, go now!</i>

1752
01:37:46,278 --> 01:37:47,362
You know what?
I hate to say it.

1753
01:37:47,404 --> 01:37:49,197
You're gonna have to wait to find out.
I know.

1754
01:37:49,239 --> 01:37:51,700
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
I love you all.

1755
01:37:52,576 --> 01:37:53,785
[all cheering]

1756
01:37:55,078 --> 01:37:56,204
[Dylan] <i>Lula, go!</i>

1757
01:37:56,246 --> 01:37:58,373
[stammers]
I have to go.

1758
01:38:11,595 --> 01:38:12,637
[all cheering]

1759
01:38:17,183 --> 01:38:21,438
[Cowan] Out of the way, FBI!
Move, move, move! Go!

1760
01:38:21,479 --> 01:38:23,231
Get some men in that park!

1761
01:38:23,273 --> 01:38:24,441
Men in the park, now!

1762
01:38:24,482 --> 01:38:26,651
[Thaddeus]
You gonna fill up on appetizers?

1763
01:38:26,693 --> 01:38:29,362
Or save room for
the main course?

1764
01:38:29,404 --> 01:38:31,239
Where the hell
are the Horsemen?

1765
01:38:31,281 --> 01:38:32,574
You can chase them
all you want,

1766
01:38:32,616 --> 01:38:35,118
you're just gonna wind up
holding your own tails.

1767
01:38:36,077 --> 01:38:38,913
Or, you can let them
come to you.

1768
01:38:38,955 --> 01:38:40,582
So, what's it gonna be?

1769
01:38:40,624 --> 01:38:41,791
Chase them?

1770
01:38:42,751 --> 01:38:44,169
Or make a deal with me?

1771
01:38:50,592 --> 01:38:52,427
Again? How did we
get found out again?

1772
01:38:52,469 --> 01:38:54,262
It's fine, it's fine.
We'll just cut to the finale.

1773
01:38:54,304 --> 01:38:55,847
- Where's Merritt?
- Fine. I don't know.

1774
01:38:55,889 --> 01:38:56,931
I'm here.

1775
01:38:56,973 --> 01:38:58,808
- Where's Lula?
- I'm right here!

1776
01:38:58,850 --> 01:39:00,769
What the hell happened?

1777
01:39:00,810 --> 01:39:02,729
- My goddamn brother happened.
- Don't worry about it.

1778
01:39:02,771 --> 01:39:04,272
We just gotta get to the destination.

1779
01:39:04,314 --> 01:39:06,274
- Lula, can you handle that thing?
- I can ride it.

1780
01:39:06,316 --> 01:39:08,360
Have you asked the guys
that question, or just me?

1781
01:39:08,401 --> 01:39:09,694
- Yeah, good point.
- Let's go!

1782
01:39:09,736 --> 01:39:10,862
No, Jack.

1783
01:39:15,492 --> 01:39:16,534
Shit!

1784
01:39:19,454 --> 01:39:20,914
[Dylan]
Jack's down. We gotta get him.

1785
01:39:24,250 --> 01:39:25,335
Come on, move!

1786
01:39:30,757 --> 01:39:33,051
- [Atlas] Jack! Go, go!
- [Lula] That's the brake.

1787
01:39:33,093 --> 01:39:34,719
That's the gas.
You'll figure it out.

1788
01:39:34,761 --> 01:39:36,471
Come on, follow me!

1789
01:39:37,722 --> 01:39:38,765
That's it?

1790
01:39:43,311 --> 01:39:46,022
[groaning]

1791
01:39:55,365 --> 01:39:56,992
- Hey, ready?
- Yeah!

1792
01:40:03,790 --> 01:40:05,166
Get on.

1793
01:40:08,962 --> 01:40:11,131
- Yeah!
- Okay, guys, I'm coming!

1794
01:40:11,172 --> 01:40:13,508
Whoa! Jesus!

1795
01:40:14,926 --> 01:40:16,720
- I'm coming!
- [tires screeching]

1796
01:40:16,761 --> 01:40:17,929
[yelping]

1797
01:40:21,850 --> 01:40:23,143
[groaning]

1798
01:40:24,811 --> 01:40:26,688
- [thug 1] Get up! Come on!
- Okay.

1799
01:40:26,730 --> 01:40:27,981
[guns cocking]

1800
01:40:28,023 --> 01:40:29,274
[groans] You got me.

1801
01:40:29,315 --> 01:40:31,526
Those things are really dangerous!

1802
01:40:33,236 --> 01:40:35,488
- [thug 1] Come on!
- [thug 2] Go!

1803
01:40:37,240 --> 01:40:39,451
[thug 3]
Get him in! Move it!

1804
01:40:43,830 --> 01:40:45,540
- [Austin] What is happening?
- [beeping]

1805
01:40:45,582 --> 01:40:47,876
Where are they?

1806
01:40:47,917 --> 01:40:49,961
They should be
arriving any second.

1807
01:40:51,212 --> 01:40:53,673
That is, if they're gonna
get here by midnight.

1808
01:41:02,849 --> 01:41:04,768
[Chase] Ah!

1809
01:41:05,935 --> 01:41:08,354
Okay, feeling fear.

1810
01:41:08,688 --> 01:41:11,399
Fear. Anger, anger.

1811
01:41:12,067 --> 01:41:15,111
- Oh, full house!
- That's enough.

1812
01:41:16,696 --> 01:41:18,114
[Chase] I was done.

1813
01:41:19,032 --> 01:41:23,161
So nice to see you all again.

1814
01:41:23,203 --> 01:41:28,750
But since we're such old friends,
let's skip the formalities.

1815
01:41:29,709 --> 01:41:34,506
One of you
has something we require.

1816
01:41:36,132 --> 01:41:37,801
So give it over.

1817
01:41:45,975 --> 01:41:48,269
Nothing at all?

1818
01:41:49,479 --> 01:41:51,981
- Really?
- [scoffs]

1819
01:41:53,733 --> 01:41:55,151
Sit down!

1820
01:41:59,364 --> 01:42:00,865
[brakes screeching]

1821
01:42:02,325 --> 01:42:03,785
[Walter] Let's go, let's go!

1822
01:42:04,994 --> 01:42:06,371
Let's go, let's go!

1823
01:42:06,412 --> 01:42:09,040
Hurry up and move them quickly
before they can do anything.

1824
01:42:09,082 --> 01:42:10,291
Get those lights off me!

1825
01:42:16,047 --> 01:42:17,632
[Walter] Get on the plane!

1826
01:42:19,634 --> 01:42:21,845
[Lula] Ow! Hey!

1827
01:42:24,430 --> 01:42:25,473
[Walter] Get on the plane!

1828
01:42:35,066 --> 01:42:36,359
- Hey!
- Whoa, whoa, hey!

1829
01:42:36,401 --> 01:42:38,319
Yeah, uh, take off immediately.

1830
01:42:40,238 --> 01:42:41,656
[groans]

1831
01:42:41,698 --> 01:42:44,367
You know, you make it almost too easy?

1832
01:42:44,409 --> 01:42:48,121
I mean, even your hilarious attempts
to make yourselves unpredictable,

1833
01:42:48,163 --> 01:42:50,039
just follow the same pattern each time.

1834
01:42:50,081 --> 01:42:52,125
Set up, set up, set up.

1835
01:42:52,166 --> 01:42:53,459
[gasps] Big reveal.

1836
01:42:53,501 --> 01:42:55,920
Which tonight was going
to be stroke of midnight,

1837
01:42:55,962 --> 01:42:58,715
middle of the Thames?
Tell me if I'm warm.

1838
01:43:03,595 --> 01:43:07,432
Well, there will be a big reveal,
and it will come now.

1839
01:43:09,142 --> 01:43:12,270
The stick, dear boy.

1840
01:43:12,812 --> 01:43:14,105
- No.
- [Walter] Fine.

1841
01:43:14,647 --> 01:43:16,900
Start with her.

1842
01:43:16,941 --> 01:43:19,277
- [yelps]
- Whoa, whoa, hey, hey, hey!

1843
01:43:21,446 --> 01:43:24,866
- Give it to him.
- Danny, give him the card.

1844
01:43:24,908 --> 01:43:26,784
- Just give it to him.
- [Jack] Danny, come on.

1845
01:43:36,794 --> 01:43:37,962
We'll have a closer look.

1846
01:43:40,965 --> 01:43:42,884
[thunder rumbling]

1847
01:43:46,387 --> 01:43:48,389
Okay, I owe you an apology.

1848
01:43:48,431 --> 01:43:50,767
Leader, you should have
planned an escape, okay?

1849
01:43:50,808 --> 01:43:52,435
- This is the both of us.
- Okay, it's the both of us.

1850
01:43:52,477 --> 01:43:54,020
- Guys, come on!
- Come on, stop!

1851
01:43:54,062 --> 01:43:56,898
- You, to save your little girlfriend!
- To save my...

1852
01:43:56,940 --> 01:43:59,233
- He had a knife to her head!
- I'm a Horseman, you dick!

1853
01:43:59,275 --> 01:44:00,777
All right, you know what?
This is not the time!

1854
01:44:00,818 --> 01:44:02,278
And you, what's your deal, man?

1855
01:44:02,320 --> 01:44:04,489
Look, they're not gonna get blood
all over the seats.

1856
01:44:04,530 --> 01:44:06,199
They're probably gonna
throw us out of the plane.

1857
01:44:06,241 --> 01:44:07,575
- Really?
- I'm sorry to interrupt,

1858
01:44:07,617 --> 01:44:09,744
but I just have to
say congratulations.

1859
01:44:09,786 --> 01:44:11,037
And thank you!

1860
01:44:12,580 --> 01:44:13,831
It's real.

1861
01:44:13,873 --> 01:44:15,333
[Lula] What?

1862
01:44:15,375 --> 01:44:16,918
[whispers] It's real?

1863
01:44:18,586 --> 01:44:19,671
Bring them through.

1864
01:44:19,712 --> 01:44:20,838
Did you say it's real?

1865
01:44:20,880 --> 01:44:21,923
[Jack]
What is he talking about?

1866
01:44:21,965 --> 01:44:23,216
Move!

1867
01:44:23,258 --> 01:44:24,801
Well done, my boy.

1868
01:44:28,638 --> 01:44:31,099
Cote Du Marisule champagne.

1869
01:44:31,140 --> 01:44:35,269
It's the most expensive bottle on Earth.

1870
01:44:36,145 --> 01:44:38,314
$1.2 million.

1871
01:44:38,356 --> 01:44:42,402
And I saved it just for this occasion.

1872
01:44:42,443 --> 01:44:46,739
Honestly, same bottle,
Liquor Shack, 700K.

1873
01:44:46,781 --> 01:44:49,909
Hey. You got what you wanted.

1874
01:44:49,951 --> 01:44:52,537
So, does this mean
you're letting us go?

1875
01:44:52,578 --> 01:44:55,540
Knowing what you
know about us? No.

1876
01:44:55,581 --> 01:44:59,294
- You sure?
- Chase, what shall we do?

1877
01:45:01,045 --> 01:45:03,256
Toss them out.

1878
01:45:03,298 --> 01:45:05,883
Get your last words
in quickly, everybody!

1879
01:45:05,925 --> 01:45:07,760
- [protesting]
- [operatic music playing]

1880
01:45:07,802 --> 01:45:11,264
- No! Come on! No!
- Farewell.

1881
01:45:11,597 --> 01:45:13,850
[Lula] Oh, God! No!

1882
01:45:15,101 --> 01:45:17,520
Wait! I just wanna say...

1883
01:45:17,562 --> 01:45:19,856
I came into the world
with the wrong family,

1884
01:45:19,897 --> 01:45:21,899
but I'm leaving with the right one.

1885
01:45:21,941 --> 01:45:23,526
I love you guys!

1886
01:45:23,568 --> 01:45:24,652
- No!
- No, no, no!

1887
01:45:26,446 --> 01:45:28,906
This is how I kicked
you out of the womb.

1888
01:45:28,948 --> 01:45:30,074
[Merritt] No!

1889
01:45:30,116 --> 01:45:31,534
- [Merritt screams]
- [Dylan shouts]

1890
01:45:31,576 --> 01:45:32,952
Who's next?

1891
01:45:34,329 --> 01:45:35,496
[Dylan screams]

1892
01:45:39,083 --> 01:45:40,960
[Lula] No, wait! Let me go!

1893
01:45:41,002 --> 01:45:43,379
[struggling] Let go of me!

1894
01:45:43,421 --> 01:45:45,757
No, no, no!

1895
01:45:45,798 --> 01:45:47,508
- Let me go!
- Toss her!

1896
01:45:49,886 --> 01:45:52,847
[laughing] Oh, God!

1897
01:45:52,889 --> 01:45:55,933
Hurry up and shut that door!
It's getting cold in here.

1898
01:45:55,975 --> 01:45:57,935
Okay, hit the road, Jack!

1899
01:46:01,189 --> 01:46:02,523
[Jack screaming]

1900
01:46:03,524 --> 01:46:04,692
No, no, no!

1901
01:46:06,069 --> 01:46:08,362
[Chase] A lot of brain,
but not enough brawn.

1902
01:46:08,404 --> 01:46:09,906
[Atlas screaming]

1903
01:46:12,116 --> 01:46:13,159
Oh, that was fun!

1904
01:46:15,995 --> 01:46:19,040
Cheers! Well done, my boy.

1905
01:46:21,793 --> 01:46:22,835
[spits]

1906
01:46:23,503 --> 01:46:24,879
Um...

1907
01:46:24,921 --> 01:46:27,131
No, is it supposed to taste like that?

1908
01:46:27,215 --> 01:46:28,716
No, it is not.

1909
01:46:45,942 --> 01:46:48,486
[engines powering down]

1910
01:46:48,528 --> 01:46:50,113
What the hell is going on?

1911
01:46:54,659 --> 01:46:56,786
[all laughing]

1912
01:47:00,081 --> 01:47:02,375
[Merritt]
Okay, come pick them up!

1913
01:47:03,042 --> 01:47:04,794
- Come on.
- [Jack] Come on out.

1914
01:47:16,514 --> 01:47:18,015
[crowd cheering]

1915
01:47:18,057 --> 01:47:21,936
[announcer]
<i>Ladies and gentlemen... The Horsemen!</i>

1916
01:47:21,978 --> 01:47:24,021
[cheering continues]

1917
01:47:42,248 --> 01:47:44,542
<i>No, you should feel pretty
good about yourself, man.</i>

1918
01:47:44,584 --> 01:47:48,171
<i>You predicted it correctly.
The Thames, stroke of midnight.</i>

1919
01:47:48,212 --> 01:47:50,047
<i>New Year's Eve. Happy New Year!</i>

1920
01:47:50,089 --> 01:47:52,258
[crowd cheering]

1921
01:47:57,054 --> 01:47:58,347
Unbelievable!

1922
01:47:58,389 --> 01:47:59,765
- We are moving now.
- The whole thing just changed.

1923
01:47:59,807 --> 01:48:02,602
- All backup into position stat!
- We're on the move.

1924
01:48:04,061 --> 01:48:06,314
- You're staying here!
- Of course.

1925
01:48:13,529 --> 01:48:15,531
[Austin]
Move! Move! Out of the way!

1926
01:48:15,573 --> 01:48:17,825
[Atlas]
Wow! Thank you very much, London!

1927
01:48:17,867 --> 01:48:22,205
We would like to acknowledge not just
our old friend, Arthur Tressler.

1928
01:48:22,246 --> 01:48:24,832
But his young and very
brilliant son, Walter Mabry.

1929
01:48:24,874 --> 01:48:27,335
Who has performed one of the
greatest feats of illusion

1930
01:48:27,376 --> 01:48:29,045
even we have ever seen.

1931
01:48:29,086 --> 01:48:33,341
He has, amazingly, brought
himself back from the dead!

1932
01:48:33,382 --> 01:48:36,052
- [crowd laughing]
- [Merritt] But before he did that,

1933
01:48:36,093 --> 01:48:37,470
he revealed someone.

1934
01:48:37,512 --> 01:48:42,683
And we think it only right
to give him a proper introduction.

1935
01:48:42,725 --> 01:48:46,771
He is our friend and he is our leader.
Dylan Shrike!

1936
01:48:46,812 --> 01:48:48,856
- Get over here!
- [Lula] Yeah!

1937
01:48:48,898 --> 01:48:50,441
[crowd cheering]

1938
01:48:54,695 --> 01:48:56,781
[Dylan] So, normally

1939
01:48:56,822 --> 01:49:01,577
only the magician, his assistant,
and a few trusted stage hands

1940
01:49:01,619 --> 01:49:03,871
know the secret of a trick.

1941
01:49:03,913 --> 01:49:06,958
But tonight, however, in this effect,

1942
01:49:06,999 --> 01:49:10,127
all of you people
around the Thames here.

1943
01:49:10,169 --> 01:49:14,840
And since we're streaming live,
everyone around the world

1944
01:49:14,882 --> 01:49:17,426
already knows everything.

1945
01:49:17,468 --> 01:49:21,597
And only these fellows
here are the ones left in the dark.

1946
01:49:21,639 --> 01:49:24,600
So let's see how closely
you were watching our shows.

1947
01:49:24,642 --> 01:49:28,396
Remember when we were playing
"Find the Lady," and I said

1948
01:49:28,437 --> 01:49:30,398
<i>that we used a Barry Trap.</i>

1949
01:49:31,148 --> 01:49:34,777
<i>Some classic switches
and a few duplicates?</i>

1950
01:49:34,819 --> 01:49:38,364
<i>Well, that's how we switched
the driver of the truck.</i>

1951
01:49:39,282 --> 01:49:41,367
[grunts]

1952
01:49:41,409 --> 01:49:43,703
<i>Which took us to a duplicate hangar</i>

1953
01:49:43,744 --> 01:49:46,330
<i>where we used your need to rush,</i>

1954
01:49:46,372 --> 01:49:49,417
<i>and your fear of being seen
let you do the work for us.</i>

1955
01:49:49,458 --> 01:49:51,294
Get those lights off me!

1956
01:49:52,545 --> 01:49:56,841
So, the airplane.
How did we get it to fly?

1957
01:49:57,883 --> 01:50:02,722
<i>[Atlas] Well, we used fans,
and lights and rain machines.</i>

1958
01:50:02,763 --> 01:50:04,599
[crowd cheering]

1959
01:50:06,142 --> 01:50:07,893
[laughing]

1960
01:50:07,935 --> 01:50:12,607
Obviously, all of this was
reliant on us getting caught.

1961
01:50:12,648 --> 01:50:13,983
But we needed to make sure

1962
01:50:14,025 --> 01:50:16,152
that you would do exactly
what we needed you to do

1963
01:50:16,193 --> 01:50:17,737
once you did catch us.

1964
01:50:17,778 --> 01:50:23,868
My brother Chase, who was
technical adviser to the losing team.

1965
01:50:23,909 --> 01:50:26,621
He taught us that it's
all about blind spots.

1966
01:50:26,662 --> 01:50:28,247
I know where you're going!

1967
01:50:28,289 --> 01:50:31,917
And, uh, surprises.

1968
01:50:33,711 --> 01:50:35,296
Watch it, hobo.

1969
01:50:35,338 --> 01:50:37,048
Why don't you watch
the watch I'm wearing,

1970
01:50:37,089 --> 01:50:39,759
the where of where
you're watching, and sleep!

1971
01:50:39,800 --> 01:50:43,179
It's going to be your idea to throw
the Horsemen out of the plane.

1972
01:50:43,220 --> 01:50:45,723
If all of this is
kind of confusing to you,

1973
01:50:45,765 --> 01:50:47,767
I can maybe catch you up on it later.

1974
01:50:47,808 --> 01:50:50,269
Probably see you what, three to five?

1975
01:50:51,395 --> 01:50:55,816
Come on, put it there.
Hey! Tit for tat, bro!

1976
01:50:56,317 --> 01:50:59,320
Basically, we showed them everything.

1977
01:50:59,362 --> 01:51:04,700
How you kidnapped us to steal the very
thing that is in your pocket right now.

1978
01:51:06,869 --> 01:51:08,287
Whoops!

1979
01:51:11,874 --> 01:51:14,377
[Merritt]
You know, this thing here,

1980
01:51:14,418 --> 01:51:17,922
which you said you could
use to adjust markets,

1981
01:51:17,963 --> 01:51:21,675
manipulate governments,
and spy on whomever you choose.

1982
01:51:21,717 --> 01:51:23,594
[Lula]
Also, you could, as you said,

1983
01:51:23,636 --> 01:51:26,847
control the public
from outside the grid.

1984
01:51:27,723 --> 01:51:33,062
These men destroy people's lives.

1985
01:51:33,104 --> 01:51:37,191
Spying on the world, robbing you
of your right to privacy.

1986
01:51:37,233 --> 01:51:40,528
And they do that
by hiding in the dark.

1987
01:51:40,569 --> 01:51:45,157
So, in the Horsemen tradition,
we're here to expose them.

1988
01:51:45,199 --> 01:51:50,287
Tonight, they, like all of us,

1989
01:51:50,329 --> 01:51:53,541
are finally stepping into the light.

1990
01:51:53,582 --> 01:51:55,376
[crowd cheering]

1991
01:51:57,461 --> 01:51:58,671
[Atlas] Thank you, everybody!

1992
01:51:58,713 --> 01:52:01,382
We are the Horsemen
and we will be back very soon!

1993
01:52:03,634 --> 01:52:07,680
[crowd] Five, four, three, two, one!

1994
01:52:07,722 --> 01:52:09,473
[fireworks bursting]

1995
01:52:10,057 --> 01:52:11,434
[chiming]

1996
01:52:15,104 --> 01:52:17,231
[sirens wailing]

1997
01:52:24,488 --> 01:52:27,116
- Hey, we're on the clock.
- Get a move on.

1998
01:52:30,161 --> 01:52:31,328
There they are!

1999
01:52:31,370 --> 01:52:33,456
- There's more inside.
- Don't you bloody touch me!

2000
01:52:33,497 --> 01:52:35,207
The Horsemen are over on the...

2001
01:52:37,960 --> 01:52:39,462
Oh, shit!

2002
01:52:40,087 --> 01:52:41,922
Stay with them!

2003
01:52:41,964 --> 01:52:44,008
Everybody spread out!

2004
01:52:44,049 --> 01:52:45,926
Nobody leaves this barge!

2005
01:52:47,803 --> 01:52:50,931
[Austin] Rhodes, hold it right there!
Do not move!

2006
01:52:56,562 --> 01:52:58,272
This contains everything.

2007
01:52:58,314 --> 01:53:01,442
Not just Walter and Tressler,
but all their dealings.

2008
01:53:01,484 --> 01:53:04,528
All their contacts,
the entire network.

2009
01:53:04,570 --> 01:53:06,822
And why on Earth
would I believe you?

2010
01:53:06,864 --> 01:53:10,576
I told you.
I'm the same man I've always been.

2011
01:53:10,618 --> 01:53:13,120
[Cowan] Move it! Come on!
Let's go, go, go!

2012
01:53:13,162 --> 01:53:15,998
[Chase] I'm not part of this
organization! I'm Merritt.

2013
01:53:16,040 --> 01:53:19,293
I'm a patsy!
I'm a patsy!

2014
01:53:20,169 --> 01:53:22,087
Ten minutes.

2015
01:53:23,839 --> 01:53:25,925
[Dylan] Now you're playing
the long game.

2016
01:53:38,187 --> 01:53:39,730
[helicopter hovering]

2017
01:53:39,772 --> 01:53:42,024
Dad, I promise you I will fix this.

2018
01:53:42,066 --> 01:53:44,485
You can't. Stop calling me dad.

2019
01:53:44,527 --> 01:53:48,489
There were so many women,
I have no idea whose bastard you are.

2020
01:53:48,531 --> 01:53:49,698
What?

2021
01:53:49,740 --> 01:53:52,117
- What happened?
- Thin air, gone. Come with me.

2022
01:53:52,159 --> 01:53:55,830
What're you talking about, gone?
People don't just disappear.

2023
01:53:55,871 --> 01:53:58,624
You realize that he doesn't actually
have magical powers!

2024
01:54:38,289 --> 01:54:39,748
- Hey, guys.
- Hey!

2025
01:54:39,790 --> 01:54:42,251
- Good to see you all.
- Good to see you, Li.

2026
01:54:43,335 --> 01:54:44,503
Come on in.

2027
01:54:47,715 --> 01:54:50,593
Good morning. Welcome.

2028
01:54:53,012 --> 01:54:56,599
I'm proud of you.
All of you.

2029
01:54:56,640 --> 01:55:00,185
I have a lot to show you. Come.

2030
01:55:01,395 --> 01:55:02,688
Come.

2031
01:55:13,991 --> 01:55:15,242
Dad.

2032
01:55:32,635 --> 01:55:34,303
[Thaddeus] Yes.

2033
01:55:34,345 --> 01:55:37,139
Your father and I were partners.

2034
01:55:37,181 --> 01:55:40,351
Our act was that of rivals.

2035
01:55:41,518 --> 01:55:47,191
I was the hard-eyed realist.
He was the dreamy-eyed idealist.

2036
01:55:47,232 --> 01:55:49,985
We thought it was the perfect misdirect.

2037
01:55:51,028 --> 01:55:54,740
Yes, in public, I did goad him.

2038
01:55:54,782 --> 01:55:59,662
The only thing we didn't count on
was it going so wrong.

2039
01:56:03,624 --> 01:56:05,501
Why?

2040
01:56:05,542 --> 01:56:07,336
Why didn't you ever say anything to me?

2041
01:56:07,378 --> 01:56:08,921
I don't know.

2042
01:56:10,047 --> 01:56:11,382
Give it a name.

2043
01:56:11,423 --> 01:56:14,885
Shame, guilt. Regret.

2044
01:56:18,597 --> 01:56:21,600
[Atlas] Hey, guys, uh, you might
wanna come take a look at this.

2045
01:56:23,227 --> 01:56:24,311
Hmm.

2046
01:56:25,771 --> 01:56:27,022
Look.

2047
01:56:27,064 --> 01:56:28,899
[Dylan]
<i>I put you in jail, man.</i>

2048
01:56:28,941 --> 01:56:31,318
Why didn't you
say something then?

2049
01:56:31,360 --> 01:56:34,405
Well, you know, I was going to.

2050
01:56:34,446 --> 01:56:39,118
But then, you were so quick to show
your personal motivations that...

2051
01:56:40,369 --> 01:56:43,789
Well, quite frankly
it spoiled the trick for me.

2052
01:56:43,831 --> 01:56:45,165
I showed my weakness.

2053
01:56:45,207 --> 01:56:48,043
Well, it showed you weren't ready.

2054
01:56:48,085 --> 01:56:50,754
But when you came back to my cell,

2055
01:56:50,796 --> 01:56:55,259
you had let go of your
30-year vendetta against me...

2056
01:56:56,218 --> 01:56:57,720
...for your Horsemen.

2057
01:56:59,263 --> 01:57:04,018
<i>And I said to myself,
"That's Lionel's boy."</i>

2058
01:57:04,852 --> 01:57:08,272
<i>And I knew it was my job to see to it</i>

2059
01:57:08,313 --> 01:57:12,067
<i>that he became the magician
he was born to be.</i>

2060
01:57:12,109 --> 01:57:14,486
All that was left then was...

2061
01:57:16,196 --> 01:57:17,573
For me to hit bottom.

2062
01:57:18,323 --> 01:57:23,203
So the safe, my father's wristwatch,
that was all you?

2063
01:57:25,956 --> 01:57:29,334
<i>Walter and Tressler,
were they in on it too?</i>

2064
01:57:29,376 --> 01:57:32,254
[Thaddeus] <i>Oh, we knew
Walter was in hiding.</i>

2065
01:57:32,296 --> 01:57:36,049
<i>The Octa show was a setup
to expose him to the public.</i>

2066
01:57:37,718 --> 01:57:41,221
<i>And you were right
about the Horsemen.</i>

2067
01:57:41,263 --> 01:57:46,351
<i>They needed to learn to work together
like a single organism.</i>

2068
01:57:53,984 --> 01:57:56,653
Now I know why
you look so familiar.

2069
01:57:56,695 --> 01:57:58,322
You're the Horsemen, aren't you?

2070
01:58:00,199 --> 01:58:01,283
[chuckles]

2071
01:58:04,536 --> 01:58:05,954
[Lula chuckles]

2072
01:58:05,996 --> 01:58:07,456
Okay.

2073
01:58:07,498 --> 01:58:09,583
[Dylan] <i>But that can't be
what all this is about.</i>

2074
01:58:09,625 --> 01:58:14,171
You know, the best tricks
work on many levels.

2075
01:58:14,213 --> 01:58:18,217
And the deepest one,
for me, at least,

2076
01:58:18,258 --> 01:58:21,094
is this moment right here.

2077
01:58:24,681 --> 01:58:26,225
I'm sorry, Dylan.

2078
01:58:26,850 --> 01:58:29,394
I miss your father.

2079
01:58:29,436 --> 01:58:32,981
Thirty years is a long time to drag
something around, isn't it?

2080
01:58:33,023 --> 01:58:34,733
Yes, it is.

2081
01:58:44,660 --> 01:58:45,953
So, now what?

2082
01:58:48,372 --> 01:58:51,291
- Now I'm about out of moves.
- Oh...

2083
01:58:51,333 --> 01:58:52,709
And I'm tired.

2084
01:58:52,751 --> 01:58:55,129
Come on, you're the one who said
that you believe that this road

2085
01:58:55,170 --> 01:58:57,172
led to the great wizard
behind the curtain.

2086
01:58:57,214 --> 01:58:58,298
I did.

2087
01:58:58,340 --> 01:59:00,509
And that you'd finally
get to look him in the eyes.

2088
01:59:01,885 --> 01:59:03,595
I am.

2089
01:59:07,224 --> 01:59:08,267
[chuckles]

2090
01:59:09,351 --> 01:59:11,854
It's your game now.

2091
01:59:11,895 --> 01:59:14,523
You play it however you see fit.

2092
01:59:15,732 --> 01:59:21,613
My suggestion, however, is that
you find yourself a successor.

2093
01:59:21,655 --> 01:59:23,574
Hi. Okay, so, um...

2094
01:59:23,615 --> 01:59:26,952
Well, obviously,
we have a few questions. Right?

2095
01:59:26,994 --> 01:59:29,538
Uh... By "a few,"
I think he means, like, five million.

2096
01:59:29,580 --> 01:59:31,165
- Yeah.
- Well.

2097
01:59:31,206 --> 01:59:33,083
Good luck to you all.

2098
01:59:33,125 --> 01:59:34,793
- Okay. See, that's not fair.
- What!

2099
01:59:34,835 --> 01:59:35,961
- Come on.
- That's not right.

2100
01:59:36,003 --> 01:59:37,337
That's gonna make me really angry!

2101
01:59:37,379 --> 01:59:38,589
- [all chattering]
- Not right now.

2102
01:59:38,630 --> 01:59:40,299
Oh, um, by the way...

2103
01:59:42,467 --> 01:59:45,012
Pay no attention to the curtain.

2104
01:59:47,890 --> 01:59:49,266
There is a curtain.

2105
01:59:49,308 --> 01:59:50,684
Go, go, go.

2106
02:00:00,027 --> 02:00:04,531
[Thaddeus] <i>Seeing is believing.
But is it truth?</i>

2107
02:00:04,573 --> 02:00:07,242
<i>Depends on your point of view.</i>

2108
02:00:07,284 --> 02:00:09,828
<i>Are you listening, Horsemen?</i>

2109
02:00:09,870 --> 02:00:14,249
<i>When you emerge, and you will,</i>

2110
02:00:14,291 --> 02:00:17,461
<i>I will be there waiting.</i>

2111
02:00:17,502 --> 02:00:23,133
<i>Because mark my words,
you will get what's coming to you</i>

2112
02:00:23,175 --> 02:00:25,844
<i>in ways you can't expect.</i>

2113
02:00:26,678 --> 02:00:29,389
<i>But very much deserve.</i>

2114
02:00:29,431 --> 02:00:32,601
<i>Because one thing I believe in</i>

2115
02:00:32,643 --> 02:00:36,563
<i>is an eye for an eye.</i>

